1
00:00:11,447 --> 00:00:14,439
(GENTLE MUSIC)

2
00:01:24,727 --> 00:01:27,719
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

3
00:01:44,487 --> 00:01:47,387
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACH)

4
00:01:47,487 --> 00:01:50,479
(MAN BREATHES HEAVILY)

5
00:01:56,047 --> 00:01:59,039
(CONTINUES BREATHING HEAVILY)

6
00:02:16,447 --> 00:02:19,439
(DISTANT CLATTERING)

7
00:02:36,287 --> 00:02:39,279
(SCRAPING AND CLATTERING)

8
00:02:47,887 --> 00:02:50,117
(MAN GROANS)

9
00:02:58,327 --> 00:03:00,045
Dad... Dad!

10
00:03:03,247 --> 00:03:05,987
(WHISPERS) Lieutenant Woodward.

11
00:03:06,087 --> 00:03:08,123
I'm your new commanding officer.

12
00:03:09,927 --> 00:03:11,827
I'm looking for Sergeant Simpson.

13
00:03:11,927 --> 00:03:15,547
You'll need to talk to Corporal
Fraser. He's up top.

14
00:03:15,647 --> 00:03:18,320
I can't seem to find my way out.

15
00:03:20,167 --> 00:03:23,667
Follow the lateral. 30 yards on,
it forks. Take the right.

16
00:03:23,767 --> 00:03:25,387
It's pretty narrow but you'll make
it.

17
00:03:25,487 --> 00:03:27,347
You'll find a shaft. Left at the top.

18
00:03:27,447 --> 00:03:30,723
25 yards, there's another shaft
that'll take you up to daylight.

19
00:03:38,807 --> 00:03:40,365
Thank you.

20
00:04:18,767 --> 00:04:20,359
VOICE: (WHISPERED) Psst.

21
00:04:44,207 --> 00:04:45,587
What's your name, sapper?

22
00:04:45,687 --> 00:04:47,187
Tiffin, sir.

23
00:04:47,287 --> 00:04:49,881
I heard something - just through
there.

24
00:05:11,007 --> 00:05:12,520
TIFFIN: Hear that?

25
00:05:13,727 --> 00:05:14,762
Listen.

26
00:05:16,447 --> 00:05:18,267
You can hear 'em digging, sir.

27
00:05:18,367 --> 00:05:20,627
- (MUFFLED TAPPING)
- There. Fritz.

28
00:05:20,727 --> 00:05:22,307
They're gonna break through.

29
00:05:22,407 --> 00:05:23,947
I swear to God,
they're bloody breaking through.

30
00:05:24,047 --> 00:05:25,526
Shh, shh!

31
00:05:30,487 --> 00:05:34,347
That sound that you heard,
was it like this?

32
00:05:34,447 --> 00:05:36,907
(TAPS TWICE RAPIDLY
AND REPEATS)

33
00:05:37,007 --> 00:05:38,486
That's it.

34
00:05:39,927 --> 00:05:41,440
That's your heart.

35
00:05:42,527 --> 00:05:44,107
What?

36
00:05:44,207 --> 00:05:45,879
Feel it.

37
00:05:47,527 --> 00:05:49,802
You're hearing your own heartbeat.

38
00:05:52,047 --> 00:05:53,587
(BIRD TWEETS)

39
00:05:53,687 --> 00:05:56,587
Make sure you clip
that little fella's claws.

40
00:05:56,687 --> 00:06:00,441
Otherwise the bugger can be dead
and still sitting on its perch.

41
00:06:15,007 --> 00:06:17,387
(BIRD TWEETS)

42
00:06:17,487 --> 00:06:19,787
When does your shift end?

43
00:06:19,887 --> 00:06:22,959
- Don't make me stay.
- (TWEETS)

44
00:06:23,967 --> 00:06:25,446
Please.

45
00:06:28,087 --> 00:06:29,759
(SAWING)

46
00:06:35,967 --> 00:06:37,947
We'll put the billiard room
through there, eh?

47
00:06:38,047 --> 00:06:39,907
You ever play billiards, Tom?

48
00:06:40,007 --> 00:06:41,427
(DISTANT SHOUTING)

49
00:06:41,527 --> 00:06:43,387
Best bloody billiard players
in the world, Australians.

50
00:06:43,487 --> 00:06:45,387
- Says who?
- Well, ask anyone.

51
00:06:45,487 --> 00:06:47,427
Best billiard players,
best horsemen, miners...

52
00:06:47,527 --> 00:06:48,507
Bullshitters?

53
00:06:48,607 --> 00:06:50,787
Keep a lid on it, you blokes.

54
00:06:50,887 --> 00:06:53,947
Percy, Ginger, go down
and relieve the Sneddons.

55
00:06:54,047 --> 00:06:55,467
Righto.

56
00:06:55,567 --> 00:06:57,187
Dug through to China by now.

57
00:06:57,287 --> 00:07:00,267
Well, I'll bring you back
some chopsticks, then, eh?

58
00:07:00,367 --> 00:07:01,947
(CHUCKLES)

59
00:07:02,047 --> 00:07:05,587
(DISTANT SHOUTING CONTINUES)

60
00:07:05,687 --> 00:07:08,587
(SHELL EXPLODES)

61
00:07:08,687 --> 00:07:11,406
(SHOUTING CONTINUES)

62
00:07:18,807 --> 00:07:19,867
(BIRD TWEETS)

63
00:07:19,967 --> 00:07:21,667
Who are you?

64
00:07:21,767 --> 00:07:25,521
I'm Lieutenant Woodward.
I'm your new C.O.

65
00:07:28,447 --> 00:07:29,880
WOODWARD: Are you Fraser?

66
00:07:31,727 --> 00:07:33,547
I'm looking for Sergeant Simpson.

67
00:07:33,647 --> 00:07:35,717
He's dead.

68
00:07:38,087 --> 00:07:39,566
Sapper?

69
00:07:41,847 --> 00:07:43,387
Norm Morris, sir.

70
00:07:43,487 --> 00:07:47,827
Except we call him ‘Pull Through'
or sometimes ‘His Lankiness'.

71
00:07:47,927 --> 00:07:50,627
- Tom Dwyer, sir.
- Billy Bacon, sir.

72
00:07:50,727 --> 00:07:52,957
- Answers to ‘Streaky'.
- (LAUGHS)

73
00:07:54,967 --> 00:07:57,627
Morris, I want you to take over
the listening post at...

74
00:07:57,727 --> 00:07:59,187
Where were we?

75
00:07:59,287 --> 00:08:00,667
102 drive left.

76
00:08:00,767 --> 00:08:02,547
WOODWARD: 102 drive left.

77
00:08:02,647 --> 00:08:04,067
Sir.

78
00:08:04,167 --> 00:08:05,827
WOODWARD: Better go with him,
Dwyer.

79
00:08:05,927 --> 00:08:07,599
Sir.

80
00:08:17,247 --> 00:08:19,124
(BIRD TWEETS)

81
00:08:32,287 --> 00:08:34,847
Show me to the officers' dugout.

82
00:08:51,727 --> 00:08:53,922
(SHELL EXPLODES)

83
00:08:55,927 --> 00:08:58,187
(ARTILLERY SHELL WHISTLES)

84
00:08:58,287 --> 00:09:00,164
(SHELL EXPLODES)

85
00:09:06,327 --> 00:09:08,427
(ARTILLERY SHELL WHISTLES)

86
00:09:08,527 --> 00:09:10,427
- (EXPLOSION)
- (MAN CRIES OUT)

87
00:09:10,527 --> 00:09:13,405
(BOMBARDMENT CONTINUES)

88
00:09:16,487 --> 00:09:19,827
TIFFIN: Sir. Sir! It's this way.

89
00:09:19,927 --> 00:09:22,307
- (EXPLOSION)
- MAN: 10 more gone.

90
00:09:22,407 --> 00:09:25,547
- Three, two...
- (ARTILLERY SHELL WHISTLES)

91
00:09:25,647 --> 00:09:27,107
(EXPLOSION)

92
00:09:27,207 --> 00:09:29,627
- MAN: Make way! Make way.
- MAN 2: Keep your head down.

93
00:09:29,727 --> 00:09:32,667
MAN: Walking wounded and blind.
Make way.

94
00:09:32,767 --> 00:09:34,627
(GUNSHOTS AND BOMBARDMENT
CONTINUE)

95
00:09:34,727 --> 00:09:36,267
MAN: Come on, move! Move!

96
00:09:36,367 --> 00:09:38,627
Walking wounded and blind.

97
00:09:38,727 --> 00:09:40,587
- MAN 2: Here you go.
- MAN: Make way.

98
00:09:40,687 --> 00:09:42,067
Come on, sir.

99
00:09:42,167 --> 00:09:43,507
(ARTILLERY SHELL WHISTLES)

100
00:09:43,607 --> 00:09:45,387
(SHELL EXPLODES)

101
00:09:45,487 --> 00:09:48,347
(MEN BELLOW IN PAIN)

102
00:09:48,447 --> 00:09:50,467
(PANICKED VOICES OVERLAP)

103
00:09:50,567 --> 00:09:52,398
MAN: (YELLS) Stretcher bearer!

104
00:09:53,407 --> 00:09:55,398
(SHRIEKS IN PAIN)

105
00:09:58,687 --> 00:10:01,427
(CONTINUES SHRIEKING)

106
00:10:01,527 --> 00:10:04,405
(BOMBARDMENT INTENSIFIES)

107
00:10:07,927 --> 00:10:09,645
(TIFFIN WAILS)

108
00:10:15,607 --> 00:10:17,027
SOLDIER: Forward!

109
00:10:17,127 --> 00:10:19,507
(MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

110
00:10:19,607 --> 00:10:21,107
(SHELL EXPLODES)

111
00:10:21,207 --> 00:10:22,587
TIFFIN: Oh! Oh!

112
00:10:22,687 --> 00:10:25,827
Tiffin! Hey, get up!

113
00:10:25,927 --> 00:10:27,838
Get up.

114
00:10:29,407 --> 00:10:31,147
- (GASPS)
- Come on, son.

115
00:10:31,247 --> 00:10:33,238
(SHELL EXPLODES)

116
00:10:33,407 --> 00:10:36,285
(TIFFIN BREATHES RAPIDLY)

117
00:10:39,167 --> 00:10:40,667
(UPPER-CLASS BRITISH ACCENT)
For God's sake, Australia.

118
00:10:40,767 --> 00:10:42,667
This is an officer's dugout.

119
00:10:42,767 --> 00:10:44,359
Woodward?

120
00:10:45,887 --> 00:10:49,387
Bill McBride. I was wondering
when I'd see you here.

121
00:10:49,487 --> 00:10:52,707
Went to mining school together.
Charters Towers boys.

122
00:10:52,807 --> 00:10:55,507
Bob Clayton, Northumberland
Fusiliers.

123
00:10:55,607 --> 00:10:57,907
Oliver Woodward,
1st Australian Tunnellers.

124
00:10:58,007 --> 00:10:59,947
An explosive man, right, Woody?

125
00:11:00,047 --> 00:11:02,356
Could blow up at any time. (LAUGHS)

126
00:11:03,647 --> 00:11:05,787
(TIFFIN CRIES OUT)

127
00:11:05,887 --> 00:11:07,366
McBRIDE: How long you been here?

128
00:11:08,367 --> 00:11:11,427
Two days. It feels like a year.

129
00:11:11,527 --> 00:11:15,042
CLAYTON: And if you survive a year,
it will feel like a bloody lifetime.

130
00:11:16,567 --> 00:11:19,867
(TIFFIN SOBS QUIETLY)

131
00:11:19,967 --> 00:11:22,187
WOODWARD: We nearly came a-gutser.

132
00:11:22,287 --> 00:11:25,067
A Fritz machine gunner
got a bead on us.

133
00:11:25,167 --> 00:11:27,747
Yeah, it's Boris. It's a farm
building.

134
00:11:27,847 --> 00:11:29,267
They call it the Red House.

135
00:11:29,367 --> 00:11:30,827
CLAYTON: Solid as bloody Gibraltar.

136
00:11:30,927 --> 00:11:33,507
Our artillery's been blasting
away at it for a week.

137
00:11:33,607 --> 00:11:35,518
Well, a direct hit'd
make a bloody difference.

138
00:11:37,687 --> 00:11:39,547
- (BOMBARDMENT CONTINUES)
- TIFFIN: Arggh!

139
00:11:39,647 --> 00:11:42,147
(CRIES LOUDLY)

140
00:11:42,247 --> 00:11:44,044
They have their own dugouts, you
know.

141
00:11:45,087 --> 00:11:46,679
A bit of air will see him right.

142
00:11:48,247 --> 00:11:50,124
You got a home, son?

143
00:11:52,407 --> 00:11:54,627
Wollongong, sir.

144
00:11:54,727 --> 00:11:56,524
Coal miner?

145
00:11:58,887 --> 00:12:01,307
- Gold, right?
- Silver, lead. Broken Hill.

146
00:12:01,407 --> 00:12:03,477
- (LOUD EXPLOSION)
- (TIFFIN SOBS)

147
00:12:05,767 --> 00:12:07,519
Sweetheart?

148
00:12:09,047 --> 00:12:10,526
Wife.

149
00:12:14,527 --> 00:12:16,707
Wife?

150
00:12:16,807 --> 00:12:18,365
Sweetheart.

151
00:12:19,807 --> 00:12:21,638
You got a photograph, Tiffin?

152
00:12:34,447 --> 00:12:37,067
She's, um...

153
00:12:37,167 --> 00:12:38,646
TIFFIN: My mum, sir.

154
00:12:41,567 --> 00:12:44,320
(McBRIDE LAUGHS)

155
00:12:46,767 --> 00:12:48,307
(McBRIDE AND WOODWARD LAUGH)

156
00:12:48,407 --> 00:12:50,875
You're not even real soldiers, are
you?

157
00:12:52,927 --> 00:12:55,387
I mean, what in God's name
are you doing here?

158
00:12:55,487 --> 00:12:58,467
Tunnelling under German lines.

159
00:12:58,567 --> 00:13:00,067
Protecting your trenches.

160
00:13:00,167 --> 00:13:01,947
- CLAYTON: From?
- WOODWARD: German tunnellers.

161
00:13:02,047 --> 00:13:03,867
CLAYTON: Who didn't show up
until you arrived

162
00:13:03,967 --> 00:13:07,387
and who are now attempting to do
the exact same bloody thing.

163
00:13:07,487 --> 00:13:09,307
Your point being?

164
00:13:09,407 --> 00:13:11,427
That it was bad enough
my men being shelled from above

165
00:13:11,527 --> 00:13:12,907
and shot at from in front.

166
00:13:13,007 --> 00:13:14,387
Now they're being mined
from underneath.

167
00:13:14,487 --> 00:13:15,707
(TIFFIN CRIES)

168
00:13:15,807 --> 00:13:17,187
If the man is wounded, Woodward,

169
00:13:17,287 --> 00:13:19,187
then for Christ's sake send him
to the dressing station.

170
00:13:19,287 --> 00:13:21,347
If he's not, then he should be
back on duty.

171
00:13:21,447 --> 00:13:22,926
Either way, he shouldn't be here.

172
00:13:23,927 --> 00:13:25,627
If you want my opinion,
neither should you.

173
00:13:25,727 --> 00:13:28,525
(TIFFIN CONTINUES CRYING)

174
00:13:34,207 --> 00:13:36,198
Good to feel wanted, eh, Tiffin?

175
00:13:37,727 --> 00:13:39,387
Wouldn't like to think we were over
here

176
00:13:39,487 --> 00:13:41,347
putting our arses on the line
for nothing.

177
00:13:41,447 --> 00:13:44,867
Clayton's alright. He's just got
the wind up him, that's all.

178
00:13:44,967 --> 00:13:46,587
Hides it well.

179
00:13:46,687 --> 00:13:49,042
People do.

180
00:13:53,407 --> 00:13:55,147
Seems a shame to waste this.

181
00:13:55,247 --> 00:13:56,667
(SHELL EXPLODES)

182
00:13:56,767 --> 00:13:59,387
(CRIES OUT)

183
00:13:59,487 --> 00:14:01,107
(IMITATES CLAYTON)
Spot of tea, old man?

184
00:14:01,207 --> 00:14:03,277
(CHUCKLES) Oh, rather!

185
00:14:04,407 --> 00:14:07,267
- (EXPLOSION)
- (CRIES) Mama!

186
00:14:07,367 --> 00:14:10,518
It's alright, Tiffin. It's alright,
son.

187
00:14:14,527 --> 00:14:16,358
(CICADAS HUM)

188
00:14:22,487 --> 00:14:24,682
(WHIP BIRD CALLS)

189
00:14:34,807 --> 00:14:37,560
Hello? Is anybody home?

190
00:14:42,087 --> 00:14:44,627
I found these two little rascals
down by the creek.

191
00:14:44,727 --> 00:14:46,187
They don't belong to you, do they?

192
00:14:46,287 --> 00:14:48,507
Oliver, is that you?

193
00:14:48,607 --> 00:14:50,467
Mrs Waddell.

194
00:14:50,567 --> 00:14:52,187
Colin, Gordon, round the back.

195
00:14:52,287 --> 00:14:54,707
Clean yourselves up before
your father gets home. Now, please.

196
00:14:54,807 --> 00:14:57,067
BOY: (FAINTLY) Hey, hey, wait.
That's not fair!

197
00:14:57,167 --> 00:14:58,627
I was hoping I might catch Moffat.

198
00:14:58,727 --> 00:15:02,347
Ah. Well, you're too late,
I'm afraid. He's joined up.

199
00:15:02,447 --> 00:15:03,747
Light Horse?

200
00:15:03,847 --> 00:15:05,267
MRS WADDELL: Of course.

201
00:15:05,367 --> 00:15:09,027
How was Papua? You know, we thought
the headhunters might have got you.

202
00:15:09,127 --> 00:15:11,147
They took one look at my head
and ran away.

203
00:15:11,247 --> 00:15:12,587
(LAUGHS)

204
00:15:12,687 --> 00:15:14,867
Tell you something, though, Mrs
Waddell,

205
00:15:14,967 --> 00:15:16,844
I could have stayed there forever.

206
00:15:18,447 --> 00:15:21,387
Just... why don't you put the nag
in the stable and come inside?

207
00:15:21,487 --> 00:15:23,107
We want to hear all your stories.

208
00:15:23,207 --> 00:15:24,799
WOODWARD: Come on, mate.

209
00:15:26,607 --> 00:15:28,086
Is that you, Isabel?

210
00:15:29,087 --> 00:15:32,467
- MR WADDELL: He's a major now.
- WOODWARD: Not surprised.

211
00:15:32,567 --> 00:15:34,467
At school, we called him ‘Captain'.

212
00:15:34,567 --> 00:15:35,947
- He was captain of everything.
- (LAUGHS)

213
00:15:36,047 --> 00:15:37,467
And were there complaints?

214
00:15:37,567 --> 00:15:39,667
- No, sir.
- No.

215
00:15:39,767 --> 00:15:41,787
- We wouldn't dare.
- Well, that's our Moffat.

216
00:15:41,887 --> 00:15:43,227
- Woody, Woody, Woody!
- Yes?

217
00:15:43,327 --> 00:15:46,467
Gordon reckons he can hold his breath
for one minute and thirteen seconds.

218
00:15:46,567 --> 00:15:48,587
- Can he really?
- Watch.

219
00:15:48,687 --> 00:15:53,467
One, two, three, four, five,

220
00:15:53,567 --> 00:15:57,027
six, seven, eight, nine, ten...

221
00:15:57,127 --> 00:15:58,867
Where's he posted now.

222
00:15:58,967 --> 00:16:01,387
Well, we don't know. Egypt, we think.

223
00:16:01,487 --> 00:16:02,947
...sixteen, seventeen...

224
00:16:03,047 --> 00:16:05,467
It'll be the engineers for you,
now, I'd imagine.

225
00:16:05,567 --> 00:16:07,707
I'd hate to think I wasted my time
training you up.

226
00:16:07,807 --> 00:16:10,747
They've asked me not to join up, sir.
They need to keep the mine running.

227
00:16:10,847 --> 00:16:12,227
Well, it's copper for the war effort.

228
00:16:12,327 --> 00:16:14,227
We can't get it out of the ground
fast enough.

229
00:16:14,327 --> 00:16:16,347
God knows how many shells
they think they'll need.

230
00:16:16,447 --> 00:16:18,227
- COLIN:34, 35...
- Well, an army needs munitions.

231
00:16:18,327 --> 00:16:21,187
No, an army needs good men,
first and foremost.

232
00:16:21,287 --> 00:16:23,107
...38, 39...
- GIRL: Woody!

233
00:16:23,207 --> 00:16:26,347
When did you get back?
How was Papua?

234
00:16:26,447 --> 00:16:29,107
What are you doing now.
Are you going to stay with us again?

235
00:16:29,207 --> 00:16:31,507
- Are you? Oh, can he, Mama?
- Just slow down a minute, Marjorie.

236
00:16:31,607 --> 00:16:32,987
And it's Mr Woodward.

237
00:16:33,087 --> 00:16:35,707
- (BIRD SHRIEKS)
- Go and play with Gordon, little man.

238
00:16:35,807 --> 00:16:38,227
- Come on, let's have a battle.
- GORDON: Alright.

239
00:16:38,327 --> 00:16:39,867
- Marjorie.
- Mr Woodward.

240
00:16:39,967 --> 00:16:42,947
The answers to your questions are -
two days ago, hot,

241
00:16:43,047 --> 00:16:44,507
I'll be working at Mt Morgan mine

242
00:16:44,607 --> 00:16:46,747
and, thank you, but I have
my own accommodation in town.

243
00:16:46,847 --> 00:16:48,547
(LAUGHS)

244
00:16:48,647 --> 00:16:52,347
- Is this for me?
- Oh, yes, but it's very silly.

245
00:16:52,447 --> 00:16:54,147
- They make them for kids.
- No, it's beautiful.

246
00:16:54,247 --> 00:16:55,965
I love it. Thank you.

247
00:16:59,407 --> 00:17:01,267
Doesn't he look wonderful?

248
00:17:01,367 --> 00:17:05,107
Some men are just born to be
in uniform, don't you think, Woody?

249
00:17:05,207 --> 00:17:07,516
- EMMA: It's Mr...
- Mr Woodward.

250
00:17:08,767 --> 00:17:10,280
Yes.

251
00:17:12,487 --> 00:17:14,067
May I have some tea, please, Mama?

252
00:17:14,167 --> 00:17:17,079
Yes, if you refill the milk jug
first.

253
00:17:21,207 --> 00:17:23,107
And you can re-tie that ribbon,
young lady.

254
00:17:23,207 --> 00:17:24,481
MARJORIE: Yes, Mama.

255
00:17:28,967 --> 00:17:30,867
She's so grown-up.

256
00:17:30,967 --> 00:17:32,467
Well, she thinks so

257
00:17:32,567 --> 00:17:35,604
but, between you and me,
I think she still has a long way to go.

258
00:17:37,167 --> 00:17:38,467
(GLASS SHATTERS)

259
00:17:38,567 --> 00:17:40,067
MARJORIE: It's alright.

260
00:17:40,167 --> 00:17:41,919
What now.

261
00:17:44,727 --> 00:17:47,827
- GORDON: Hey, I outflanked him.
- COLIN: No, you didn't.

262
00:17:47,927 --> 00:17:51,427
Actually, I believe that Colin
has outflanked yours, see?

263
00:17:51,527 --> 00:17:53,427
And my left flank moves forward...

264
00:17:53,527 --> 00:17:54,947
- Mr Woodward?
- Yes?

265
00:17:55,047 --> 00:17:58,027
- Do women ever go down mines?
- I don't think so.

266
00:17:58,127 --> 00:18:00,707
Bad luck, they reckon.

267
00:18:00,807 --> 00:18:02,147
Well, that's good

268
00:18:02,247 --> 00:18:05,387
because I don't know that I'd like
to be so deep underground.

269
00:18:05,487 --> 00:18:07,187
It must feel awfully claustrophobic.

270
00:18:07,287 --> 00:18:10,147
It's funny. I quite like it down
there.

271
00:18:10,247 --> 00:18:12,867
Really? Why?

272
00:18:12,967 --> 00:18:14,923
Snug.

273
00:18:17,007 --> 00:18:19,441
Hmm. Snug.

274
00:18:21,287 --> 00:18:23,267
- (SPITS LOUDLY)
- Marjorie!

275
00:18:23,367 --> 00:18:26,467
- Sorry, I...
- Are you OK?

276
00:18:26,567 --> 00:18:28,227
Yes, I just...

277
00:18:28,327 --> 00:18:30,841
Just go and clean yourself up
immediately.

278
00:18:33,367 --> 00:18:34,507
I'm so sorry.

279
00:18:34,607 --> 00:18:36,987
One moment she's an adult,
the next minute she's a child.

280
00:18:37,087 --> 00:18:39,806
16 is a very difficult age.

281
00:18:46,607 --> 00:18:48,907
Now, while Moffat's away,
I want you to visit whenever you can.

282
00:18:49,007 --> 00:18:50,387
- You promise me?
- I promise.

283
00:18:50,487 --> 00:18:51,715
Right.

284
00:18:52,847 --> 00:18:56,507
Mr Woodward, I hope you'll forgive
my silly indiscretion at the table.

285
00:18:56,607 --> 00:18:59,758
Of course. Think nothing of it.

286
00:19:01,487 --> 00:19:04,365
Well, goodbye, all.

287
00:19:06,527 --> 00:19:07,507
Oh!

288
00:19:07,607 --> 00:19:10,387
(HORSE WHINNIES)

289
00:19:10,487 --> 00:19:12,587
(LAUGHS)

290
00:19:12,687 --> 00:19:15,547
Marjorie Waddell, did you have
something to do with this?

291
00:19:15,647 --> 00:19:19,307
WOODWARD: No, no.
It's my own stupid fault, I'm afraid.

292
00:19:19,407 --> 00:19:21,267
He got into the lucerne this morning

293
00:19:21,367 --> 00:19:25,107
and suffered terrible flatulence
on the ride over.

294
00:19:25,207 --> 00:19:27,347
I think that's perhaps
how we got here so quickly.

295
00:19:27,447 --> 00:19:28,547
(LAUGHS)

296
00:19:28,647 --> 00:19:31,107
So, when I arrived I loosened the
girth.

297
00:19:31,207 --> 00:19:34,597
Must've forgotten to cinch it up.
Stupid of me.

298
00:19:36,367 --> 00:19:38,587
Are you sure you're not injured?

299
00:19:38,687 --> 00:19:40,882
No, I'm fine, honestly.

300
00:19:49,127 --> 00:19:51,227
Thank you for the tea, Mrs Waddell.

301
00:19:51,327 --> 00:19:53,027
Mr Waddell.

302
00:19:53,127 --> 00:19:55,243
Oliver.

303
00:19:57,527 --> 00:19:59,199
Isabel.

304
00:20:04,927 --> 00:20:06,121
(BIRD CHIRPS)

305
00:20:15,327 --> 00:20:16,601
Anything?

306
00:20:19,087 --> 00:20:21,667
There's something wrong
with this bloody candle.

307
00:20:21,767 --> 00:20:24,427
It's just making it darker.

308
00:20:24,527 --> 00:20:27,907
It's not the candle, Pull Through.
It's the air.

309
00:20:28,007 --> 00:20:30,840
Not enough oxygen for it to burn.

310
00:20:35,927 --> 00:20:38,027
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

311
00:20:38,127 --> 00:20:41,347
Oh, Jesus Christ!

312
00:20:41,447 --> 00:20:43,307
Could be worse.

313
00:20:43,407 --> 00:20:46,307
Oh, Tommo, how could it
possibly be worse?

314
00:20:46,407 --> 00:20:48,867
Well, they could send us to Hill 60.

315
00:20:48,967 --> 00:20:50,467
What's Hill 60?

316
00:20:50,567 --> 00:20:54,347
Messines Ridge, just across the
border, near ‘Wipers'.

317
00:20:54,447 --> 00:20:56,587
Blokes from the 40th
were sent off yesterday.

318
00:20:56,687 --> 00:20:58,907
Fritz has got the high ground.

319
00:20:59,007 --> 00:21:02,747
Our blokes are trying to fight in
bogs - bloody marshland.

320
00:21:02,847 --> 00:21:06,601
Trenches running like
rivers of blood, they say.

321
00:21:09,367 --> 00:21:10,987
That's just talk, probably.

322
00:21:11,087 --> 00:21:13,907
(BIRD CHIRPS)

323
00:21:14,007 --> 00:21:15,387
Shush, you little bugger.

324
00:21:15,487 --> 00:21:17,318
You'll get us all killed.

325
00:21:19,647 --> 00:21:21,126
Norm...

326
00:21:22,407 --> 00:21:24,477
- (TIMBER SNAPS)
- (MAN GASPS FOR BREATH)

327
00:21:25,487 --> 00:21:27,347
- (GUNSHOT)
- Aarggh!

328
00:21:27,447 --> 00:21:31,565
(GUNFIRE)

329
00:21:32,567 --> 00:21:34,947
Aarggh!

330
00:21:35,047 --> 00:21:37,987
Aaaarggh!

331
00:21:38,087 --> 00:21:42,524
- (LANTERN SMASHES)
- (MEN GRUNT AND STRUGGLE)

332
00:21:44,087 --> 00:21:46,027
(MAN GURGLES)

333
00:21:46,127 --> 00:21:49,563
(MAN SOBS)

334
00:21:56,287 --> 00:21:57,627
TOM: Oh, my God.

335
00:21:57,727 --> 00:22:00,027
Howd you know it wasn't me?

336
00:22:00,127 --> 00:22:02,107
Lucky guess.

337
00:22:02,207 --> 00:22:04,437
Jesus Christ.

338
00:22:24,487 --> 00:22:26,443
Is he dead?

339
00:22:29,967 --> 00:22:32,067
Call it even, eh, Tommo?

340
00:22:32,167 --> 00:22:34,237
(CHUCKLES)

341
00:22:41,767 --> 00:22:43,387
(PIGEON COOS)

342
00:22:43,487 --> 00:22:46,827
(EXPLOSION)

343
00:22:46,927 --> 00:22:48,804
- Shit!
- (PHONE RINGS)

344
00:22:52,967 --> 00:22:54,467
McBride.

345
00:22:54,567 --> 00:22:56,027
(MAN ON TELEPHONE
SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)

346
00:22:56,127 --> 00:22:57,707
Location?

347
00:22:57,807 --> 00:22:59,587
Say again.

348
00:22:59,687 --> 00:23:01,757
How many?

349
00:23:04,047 --> 00:23:05,605
Right.

350
00:23:12,847 --> 00:23:14,917
102 drive has been crumped.

351
00:23:21,527 --> 00:23:22,867
Casualties?

352
00:23:22,967 --> 00:23:26,755
Two missing - um, Morris and Dwyer.

353
00:23:33,767 --> 00:23:37,396
(BREATHES NOISILY)

354
00:23:41,327 --> 00:23:43,707
Hows the air?

355
00:23:43,807 --> 00:23:45,445
(BIRD CHIRPS)

356
00:23:55,647 --> 00:23:58,427
If they were near the face...

357
00:23:58,527 --> 00:24:01,067
Not a chance. Not a fucking chance
in the world.

358
00:24:01,167 --> 00:24:02,867
...they may have found an air pocket.

359
00:24:02,967 --> 00:24:05,227
This strata holds up sometimes.

360
00:24:05,327 --> 00:24:09,147
We struck some in Papua.
It's kind of... dense...

361
00:24:09,247 --> 00:24:11,867
(SNIFFS AND SPITS LOUDLY)

362
00:24:11,967 --> 00:24:15,467
It's pointless -
the whole miserable stunt.

363
00:24:15,567 --> 00:24:17,558
- (BIRD CHIRPS)
- Lively, boys.

364
00:24:32,887 --> 00:24:34,827
Steel soles.

365
00:24:34,927 --> 00:24:36,507
German.

366
00:24:36,607 --> 00:24:40,787
Stupid pricks.
Hear 'em coming a mile off.

367
00:24:40,887 --> 00:24:44,627
(BREATHES HEAVILY AND COUGHS)

368
00:24:44,727 --> 00:24:46,267
- MAN: Mate?
- I need you to move back.

369
00:24:46,367 --> 00:24:47,800
Mate, are you alright?

370
00:24:55,647 --> 00:24:57,507
(BREATHES NOISILY)

371
00:24:57,607 --> 00:24:59,359
Help me here.

372
00:25:11,927 --> 00:25:13,307
MAN: Aarggh!

373
00:25:13,407 --> 00:25:14,999
It's Tommo.

374
00:25:38,527 --> 00:25:41,307
(MAN COUGHS)

375
00:25:41,407 --> 00:25:43,147
Shh!

376
00:25:43,247 --> 00:25:47,240
(MAN COUGHS)

377
00:25:50,367 --> 00:25:52,787
- Boys, it's Pull Through.
- Boys? Is that you, boys?

378
00:25:52,887 --> 00:25:55,787
Hang on, Pull Through. We'll just...

379
00:25:55,887 --> 00:25:57,267
Easy.

380
00:25:57,367 --> 00:25:59,835
Can you get me out?
I thought I was a goner.

381
00:26:02,007 --> 00:26:03,347
Watch out for your specs.

382
00:26:03,447 --> 00:26:07,347
- Easy. Easy.
- (COUGHS)

383
00:26:07,447 --> 00:26:10,678
(VOMITS)

384
00:26:16,007 --> 00:26:19,587
Didn't think you'd get out of the
bloody war that easy, did you, old son?

385
00:26:19,687 --> 00:26:23,747
(SPEAKS INAUDIBLY)

386
00:26:23,847 --> 00:26:25,724
WOODWARD: Morris,
can you hear me?

387
00:26:28,287 --> 00:26:31,587
(SPEAKS INAUDIBLY)

388
00:26:31,687 --> 00:26:34,507
(BREATHES RAPIDLY) Tommo?

389
00:26:34,607 --> 00:26:36,307
- Tommo!
- Morris, can you hear me?

390
00:26:36,407 --> 00:26:38,587
Tommo! Tommo's in there.

391
00:26:38,687 --> 00:26:43,715
There's a man buried.
Tommo! Tommo! No!

392
00:26:49,567 --> 00:26:51,125
(PULL THROUGH COUGHS)

393
00:26:53,767 --> 00:26:56,467
Take Morris up
to the dressing station, Fraser.

394
00:26:56,567 --> 00:26:57,761
Come on, Pull Through.

395
00:27:10,247 --> 00:27:12,387
One arrives nearly every day -

396
00:27:12,487 --> 00:27:17,067
no stamp, no return address,
of course.

397
00:27:17,167 --> 00:27:18,587
But what do they mean?

398
00:27:18,687 --> 00:27:20,707
That I'm a coward.

399
00:27:20,807 --> 00:27:23,147
But you're not. You're staying here
and doing your duty.

400
00:27:23,247 --> 00:27:24,587
Shush now, Marjorie.

401
00:27:24,687 --> 00:27:26,267
Mr Woodward knows
how to stop the feathers.

402
00:27:26,367 --> 00:27:27,707
MARJORIE: So, you agree with them?

403
00:27:27,807 --> 00:27:30,267
Well, let's just hope
that there won't be any more.

404
00:27:30,367 --> 00:27:32,707
On the contrary,
just a few more feathers

405
00:27:32,807 --> 00:27:34,147
and I'll have a whole chicken.

406
00:27:34,247 --> 00:27:36,124
- (LAUGHS)
- WADDELL: Isabel!

407
00:27:42,407 --> 00:27:43,886
MARJORIE: Are you missing Papua?

408
00:27:48,687 --> 00:27:50,667
I worry about the local workers.

409
00:27:50,767 --> 00:27:53,187
Bougainville is just up the coast.
It's a German colony.

410
00:27:53,287 --> 00:27:54,707
If they send the German fleet down...

411
00:27:54,807 --> 00:27:57,347
Good Lord, man! What would
the Germans want with Papua?

412
00:27:57,447 --> 00:27:59,387
They've bitten off
more than they can chew in Europe.

413
00:27:59,487 --> 00:28:02,126
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

414
00:28:03,927 --> 00:28:07,840
Anyway, the word is the whole thing
will be over by Christmas.

415
00:28:11,847 --> 00:28:13,467
Marjorie, clear away the plates now.

416
00:28:13,567 --> 00:28:14,966
Yes, Mama.

417
00:28:27,207 --> 00:28:29,084
Best put those back, Woody.

418
00:28:37,007 --> 00:28:39,567
(BOY SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)

419
00:28:41,807 --> 00:28:43,479
William...

420
00:28:46,887 --> 00:28:48,707
It's Moffat.

421
00:28:48,807 --> 00:28:51,275
MARJORIE: Mama?

422
00:28:53,607 --> 00:28:56,387
Take the children to their rooms,
please, Marjorie.

423
00:28:56,487 --> 00:28:59,877
Isabel, boys, come on. Now, please.

424
00:29:07,327 --> 00:29:09,158
William, tell me.

425
00:29:11,647 --> 00:29:13,717
It's not good news, I'm afraid.

426
00:29:43,767 --> 00:29:46,725
Why would they send the Light Horse
to Gallipoli, Oliver?

427
00:29:49,207 --> 00:29:51,721
It's just cliffs, isn't it?

428
00:29:53,647 --> 00:29:55,763
Is it not all just cliffs?

429
00:29:59,807 --> 00:30:01,798
I don't know, sir.

430
00:30:07,687 --> 00:30:09,245
I don't know.

431
00:30:31,767 --> 00:30:33,227
Marjorie.

432
00:30:33,327 --> 00:30:39,067
You don't have to go.
Just because Moffat, you know...

433
00:30:39,167 --> 00:30:41,806
You don't have to go to the war.

434
00:30:47,087 --> 00:30:49,267
I just couldn't bear it.

435
00:30:49,367 --> 00:30:51,835
(SOBS)

436
00:31:15,007 --> 00:31:16,440
(MAN YELLS INDISTINCTLY)

437
00:31:17,607 --> 00:31:18,827
FRASER: The point is...

438
00:31:18,927 --> 00:31:23,547
The point is I was kaput, finished,
and he got me out.

439
00:31:23,647 --> 00:31:25,267
The point, Pull Through,
is you shouldn't have

440
00:31:25,367 --> 00:31:26,827
been there in the bloody first place.

441
00:31:26,927 --> 00:31:28,645
TIFFIN: Still don't know
what I heard, but.

442
00:31:30,287 --> 00:31:32,187
Maybe it really was me heart.

443
00:31:32,287 --> 00:31:33,867
Maybe I never heard no Germans.

444
00:31:33,967 --> 00:31:35,267
Of course you heard 'em.

445
00:31:35,367 --> 00:31:37,027
Don't make no difference.

446
00:31:37,127 --> 00:31:39,561
(FOOTSTEPS TREAD HEAVILY)

447
00:31:43,807 --> 00:31:46,067
- Oh, fuck, man.
- (ALL LAUGH)

448
00:31:46,167 --> 00:31:47,667
Good on you, Streaky.

449
00:31:47,767 --> 00:31:49,507
Courtesy of
the Northumberland Fusiliers.

450
00:31:49,607 --> 00:31:51,667
- Oh, bloody generous of 'em.
- Send 'em our regards.

451
00:31:51,767 --> 00:31:53,947
Probably not a good idea, Corp.

452
00:31:54,047 --> 00:31:56,242
(ALL LAUGH)

453
00:32:10,487 --> 00:32:11,867
MAN: Mmm.

454
00:32:11,967 --> 00:32:13,366
Tiffin?

455
00:32:18,287 --> 00:32:20,427
WALT: We was ready
to give up on you, Pull Through.

456
00:32:20,527 --> 00:32:22,867
- We wasn't.
- Well, we was.

457
00:32:22,967 --> 00:32:25,027
Well, you was. You said.

458
00:32:25,127 --> 00:32:26,907
Finish your letter, Walt,
or get some more shut-eye.

459
00:32:27,007 --> 00:32:31,547
But the Lieutenant knew about
the strata, Dad. How it holds up, like.

460
00:32:31,647 --> 00:32:32,987
And that's why we kept digging.

461
00:32:33,087 --> 00:32:37,227
The fact is Tom Dwyer's dead because
Woodward made a blue - a bad one.

462
00:32:37,327 --> 00:32:39,347
Won't be the last either.

463
00:32:39,447 --> 00:32:41,467
- He's alright, he is.
- Yeah?

464
00:32:41,567 --> 00:32:43,046
Then why'd he join late?

465
00:32:44,247 --> 00:32:46,627
Does anyone want
the last of the axle grease?

466
00:32:46,727 --> 00:32:48,307
I was over here, killing Germans,

467
00:32:48,407 --> 00:32:51,307
months before
his fuckin' number was dry.

468
00:32:51,407 --> 00:32:53,027
Evening.

469
00:32:53,127 --> 00:32:55,107
WOODWARD: Stay there.

470
00:32:55,207 --> 00:32:58,187
Surprised to see you here.

471
00:32:58,287 --> 00:33:00,147
Me hearing came back.

472
00:33:00,247 --> 00:33:03,107
Tommy doctor checked me out, couldn't
find a bloody thing wrong with me.

473
00:33:03,207 --> 00:33:04,827
Too bad.

474
00:33:04,927 --> 00:33:07,680
- Smoke?
- Yeah, thanks.

475
00:33:29,767 --> 00:33:31,041
It's bad luck.

476
00:33:32,847 --> 00:33:36,067
Bad luck lighting three smokes
with one match.

477
00:33:36,167 --> 00:33:38,307
First one, Fritz sniper sees you.

478
00:33:38,407 --> 00:33:40,227
Second one, he gets an aim.

479
00:33:40,327 --> 00:33:43,227
Third one, he blows
your fuckin' head off.

480
00:33:43,327 --> 00:33:46,187
Well, he'd be a crack shot
if he could get me down here.

481
00:33:46,287 --> 00:33:47,787
(SCATTERED LAUGHTER)

482
00:33:47,887 --> 00:33:50,481
Well, you never know
who's watchin', do you, sir?

483
00:33:55,007 --> 00:33:57,947
I'll be writing to Tom Dwyer's
family.

484
00:33:58,047 --> 00:34:01,278
If he had any possessions to send
back, bring them to my dugout.

485
00:34:03,327 --> 00:34:05,318
Officer approaching! Attention!

486
00:34:09,847 --> 00:34:12,507
- Woodward?
- Yes, sir?

487
00:34:12,607 --> 00:34:15,307
I understand you're a demolition man.

488
00:34:15,407 --> 00:34:18,067
I'm trained in mining explosives,
sir, not...

489
00:34:18,167 --> 00:34:19,507
You're aware that the Germans

490
00:34:19,607 --> 00:34:21,347
have placed a machine gun
in the Red House,

491
00:34:21,447 --> 00:34:22,907
such that they can enfilade our
trench?

492
00:34:23,007 --> 00:34:25,427
En... enfilade?

493
00:34:25,527 --> 00:34:27,067
Fire down it lengthwise.

494
00:34:27,167 --> 00:34:28,667
Oh, yes, sir.

495
00:34:28,767 --> 00:34:32,147
And how much explosive charge would
you need to demolish that building?

496
00:34:32,247 --> 00:34:33,747
Depends where you placed it, sir.

497
00:34:33,847 --> 00:34:36,027
How much would you need
to do the job properly?

498
00:34:36,127 --> 00:34:39,467
(MEN SHOUT IN THE DISTANCE)

499
00:34:39,567 --> 00:34:40,907
50 pounds.

500
00:34:41,007 --> 00:34:43,707
Do we have that in the stores
or do we have to requisition it?

501
00:34:43,807 --> 00:34:47,027
- CLAYTON: We have it on hand, sir.
- There's a listening post at 105 Drive.

502
00:34:47,127 --> 00:34:49,547
That'd put you about 70 foot from
Boris.

503
00:34:49,647 --> 00:34:52,347
If we drove north from there,
we could be under it in, what?

504
00:34:52,447 --> 00:34:56,427
Oh, three shifts, 30 foot a day -
we could do it in two or three days.

505
00:34:56,527 --> 00:34:59,147
Let's have it done before sun-up,
0400.

506
00:34:59,247 --> 00:35:01,867
Clayton, you'll have to cut
a gap in the wire.

507
00:35:01,967 --> 00:35:04,107
I'll have the artillery
give you one hour.

508
00:35:04,207 --> 00:35:07,085
- Sir.
- Sir!

509
00:35:17,407 --> 00:35:19,667
MAN: He couldn't
get out of here fast enough.

510
00:35:19,767 --> 00:35:22,707
Word is that bastard won't catch a
train in case it's going down a tunnel.

511
00:35:22,807 --> 00:35:24,467
(MEN LAUGH)

512
00:35:24,567 --> 00:35:26,797
WOODWARD: It'll mean
going over the bags...

513
00:35:28,727 --> 00:35:31,082
...crossing no-man's-land,
setting a charge.

514
00:35:32,527 --> 00:35:34,518
I'll need two men.

515
00:35:38,207 --> 00:35:39,587
I'll go, sir.

516
00:35:39,687 --> 00:35:41,279
- You don't have to, Morris.
- Want to, sir.

517
00:35:46,527 --> 00:35:48,006
FRASER: Sit down, Tiffin.

518
00:35:55,567 --> 00:35:57,523
I'll go.

519
00:36:01,527 --> 00:36:05,267
(EXPLOSIONS AND GUNFIRE)

520
00:36:05,367 --> 00:36:07,198
Here.

521
00:36:14,847 --> 00:36:17,627
(ENGLISH ACCENT) A bit out of
your element, aren't you, Australia?

522
00:36:17,727 --> 00:36:20,067
I heard you tunnelling chaps
were wombats.

523
00:36:20,167 --> 00:36:21,987
Come up for some air, have you?

524
00:36:22,087 --> 00:36:24,627
Actually, we've been invited
to blow up the Red House.

525
00:36:24,727 --> 00:36:26,877
Apparently you blokes keep missing.

526
00:36:29,127 --> 00:36:30,958
(BOTH LAUGH)

527
00:36:39,927 --> 00:36:41,918
(MACHINE GUN FIRES)

528
00:36:43,127 --> 00:36:44,799
Set the exploder up over there.

529
00:36:52,527 --> 00:36:54,827
Right. That's us.

530
00:36:54,927 --> 00:36:56,679
They'll start up again at dawn.

531
00:37:01,727 --> 00:37:03,718
You've never been over the bags
before, have you?

532
00:37:06,407 --> 00:37:08,125
Christ.

533
00:37:11,447 --> 00:37:15,227
When you get over the top,
stay low, don't bunch up.

534
00:37:15,327 --> 00:37:17,147
If a flare goes up, freeze.

535
00:37:17,247 --> 00:37:20,147
Don't bloody go to ground. Fritz
machine-gunners look for movement.

536
00:37:20,247 --> 00:37:23,667
Keep one eye closed
until the flare drops -

537
00:37:23,767 --> 00:37:25,439
then you'll see better
when it's dark again.

538
00:37:28,687 --> 00:37:30,279
Thank you.

539
00:37:32,487 --> 00:37:34,747
- Did your boys cut the wire?
- Yeah.

540
00:37:34,847 --> 00:37:37,107
Lieutenant Clayton took
a couple of lads out earlier.

541
00:37:37,207 --> 00:37:40,404
He ain't back yet. I'll cover you.

542
00:37:42,447 --> 00:37:43,926
Let's go.

543
00:37:54,287 --> 00:37:56,323
(FIRES GUN)

544
00:38:13,367 --> 00:38:15,358
(FLARE HISSES)

545
00:38:33,007 --> 00:38:34,520
- (GUN FIRES)
- MAN: Fuck!

546
00:38:45,047 --> 00:38:46,387
FRASER: It's Boris, alright.

547
00:38:46,487 --> 00:38:48,921
He hasn't spotted us, but.
The bastard's just trying his luck.

548
00:38:49,967 --> 00:38:52,356
WOODWARD: Right. Let's go.

549
00:39:06,607 --> 00:39:09,201
(FLARE HISSES)

550
00:39:13,327 --> 00:39:15,283
(GUN FIRES)

551
00:39:16,287 --> 00:39:18,243
Ready?

552
00:39:40,367 --> 00:39:42,198
(SOLDIERS SPEAK GERMAN)

553
00:39:43,207 --> 00:39:45,004
We'll have to go under.

554
00:39:47,327 --> 00:39:48,965
There must be a cellar.

555
00:39:53,407 --> 00:39:55,602
(GUN FIRES)

556
00:40:13,127 --> 00:40:16,961
(SOLDIERS SPEAK GERMAN)

557
00:40:50,447 --> 00:40:52,881
(GUN FIRES)

558
00:41:09,167 --> 00:41:12,398
(SOLDIERS CONTINUE
SPEAKING GERMAN)

559
00:41:13,647 --> 00:41:15,267
- (BRICK FALLS)
- (SOLDIERS SHOUT IN GERMAN)

560
00:41:15,367 --> 00:41:16,880
(GUN FIRES)

561
00:41:21,487 --> 00:41:22,966
(SOLDIERS SPEAK GERMAN)

562
00:42:19,847 --> 00:42:21,360
Corp!

563
00:42:25,927 --> 00:42:27,987
FRASER: Oh, Jesus Christ.

564
00:42:28,087 --> 00:42:30,647
- WOODWARD: What?
- We're short.

565
00:42:32,647 --> 00:42:35,036
WOODWARD: Do you think
you can get the exploder?

566
00:42:37,527 --> 00:42:39,187
Sir, we could try again tonight.

567
00:42:39,287 --> 00:42:42,467
They'll have found the charge
by then. Can you get it?

568
00:42:42,567 --> 00:42:44,307
PULL THROUGH: I think so.

569
00:42:44,407 --> 00:42:46,787
Stay on your bloody stomach

570
00:42:46,887 --> 00:42:50,027
and when you get close, give
a low whistle to identify yourself.

571
00:42:50,127 --> 00:42:52,357
The Tommies see any movement.

572
00:42:53,527 --> 00:42:55,147
(GUN FIRES)

573
00:42:55,247 --> 00:42:56,760
Oh!

574
00:43:01,927 --> 00:43:05,840
(BOTH PANT)

575
00:43:07,807 --> 00:43:09,923
(FLARE HISSES)

576
00:43:15,967 --> 00:43:17,787
Who's the fastest man in our company?

577
00:43:17,887 --> 00:43:19,667
You need a runner?

578
00:43:19,767 --> 00:43:21,427
Yes.

579
00:43:21,527 --> 00:43:24,627
Yeah, Streaky's bloody quick.

580
00:43:24,727 --> 00:43:26,365
(MAN GRUNTS)

581
00:43:29,887 --> 00:43:31,366
Christ.

582
00:43:36,047 --> 00:43:37,707
FRASER: Is it one of our boys?

583
00:43:37,807 --> 00:43:40,707
WOODWARD:
There's no way of knowing.

584
00:43:40,807 --> 00:43:42,638
Poor bastard.

585
00:43:44,767 --> 00:43:46,107
Stay here.

586
00:43:46,207 --> 00:43:48,307
Morris will be back any minute now.

587
00:43:48,407 --> 00:43:49,747
FRASER: Wait.

588
00:43:49,847 --> 00:43:51,803
Wait, sir!

589
00:43:55,487 --> 00:43:57,000
Who are you?

590
00:44:07,047 --> 00:44:08,605
- Clayton?
- (GRUNTS)

591
00:44:10,247 --> 00:44:12,667
- Where did they get you?
- (GRUNTS)

592
00:44:12,767 --> 00:44:15,964
- Mary, Mary.
- (MACHINE GUN FIRES)

593
00:44:18,247 --> 00:44:21,627
You're set now, mate. We're gonna
get you home to your Mary.

594
00:44:21,727 --> 00:44:24,467
- (GRUNTS)
- OK? Everything's OK.

595
00:44:24,567 --> 00:44:26,717
Come on. Come on, Captain.

596
00:44:27,727 --> 00:44:28,955
Come on.

597
00:44:31,047 --> 00:44:32,116
WOODWARD: Help.

598
00:44:35,327 --> 00:44:37,477
(GRUNTS)

599
00:44:42,087 --> 00:44:43,600
(MACHINE GUN FIRES)

600
00:44:48,447 --> 00:44:49,827
Field dressing.

601
00:44:49,927 --> 00:44:53,761
- Where is he injured?
- Left leg, above the knee.

602
00:44:58,487 --> 00:44:59,920
(YELLS)

603
00:45:14,047 --> 00:45:15,844
(MACHINE GUN FIRES)

604
00:45:17,047 --> 00:45:18,560
Christ.

605
00:45:25,647 --> 00:45:27,956
No! Wait.

606
00:45:35,367 --> 00:45:39,042
- Bastard's got a pattern.
- Thanks, mate.

607
00:45:44,407 --> 00:45:45,886
Captain.

608
00:46:10,087 --> 00:46:12,078
Just pray they haven't broken.

609
00:46:25,487 --> 00:46:27,398
(LAUGHS)

610
00:46:31,207 --> 00:46:33,004
(GRUNTS) Thank you.

611
00:46:36,887 --> 00:46:39,685
Sir, are you wounded?

612
00:46:41,367 --> 00:46:43,244
I don't think so.

613
00:47:33,927 --> 00:47:36,760
- Hello, Mr Woodward.
- Marjorie.

614
00:47:38,127 --> 00:47:39,640
How is everything at home?

615
00:47:40,927 --> 00:47:42,440
We're coping.

616
00:47:56,927 --> 00:47:59,147
They've formed a mining battalion.

617
00:47:59,247 --> 00:48:01,667
It's a secret, I think.

618
00:48:01,767 --> 00:48:04,787
They're looking for miners
and engineers.

619
00:48:04,887 --> 00:48:06,320
I've joined up.

620
00:48:09,567 --> 00:48:11,387
In a few weeks,
I'll be leaving for training,

621
00:48:11,487 --> 00:48:13,921
and after that, I expect
I'll be sent off to the war.

622
00:48:15,847 --> 00:48:17,724
I see.

623
00:48:25,407 --> 00:48:29,387
Marjorie, I'm nearly 10 years
your senior.

624
00:48:29,487 --> 00:48:31,507
You're only 16.

625
00:48:31,607 --> 00:48:33,279
I'll be 17 in a month.

626
00:48:35,487 --> 00:48:38,126
I signed the papers this morning.

627
00:48:45,687 --> 00:48:49,077
I would like to ask you if I could
write to you while I was away.

628
00:48:57,327 --> 00:48:59,716
I would be happy
if you wrote to me...

629
00:49:02,327 --> 00:49:05,507
...but if you're asking me
to wait for your return,

630
00:49:05,607 --> 00:49:07,643
then you must first ask my father.

631
00:49:17,407 --> 00:49:19,841
Thank you for taking
the trouble to see me.

632
00:49:36,447 --> 00:49:37,960
Come in close.

633
00:49:41,287 --> 00:49:44,947
If they're going to put on a big
push, it'll happen right now.

634
00:49:45,047 --> 00:49:46,987
They're gonna hit us
where we're most vulnerable.

635
00:49:47,087 --> 00:49:48,467
FRASER: Our left flank.

636
00:49:48,567 --> 00:49:52,427
Whatever happens, we need
to hold our line, understand?

637
00:49:52,527 --> 00:49:54,667
ENGLISH SOLDIER:
You convicts gonna play or what?

638
00:49:54,767 --> 00:49:59,966
MAN: OK, lads. Kick it off.
Three points all. Next to score wins.

639
00:50:01,287 --> 00:50:02,627
- MAN 2: Come on, Australia.
- (WHISTLE BLOWS)

640
00:50:02,727 --> 00:50:03,947
MAN: Let's go!

641
00:50:04,047 --> 00:50:06,787
MAN: Get right, boys. Go right.
Tiffin, get in there!

642
00:50:06,887 --> 00:50:09,427
Boom, boom, out right!

643
00:50:09,527 --> 00:50:11,107
Go, go, go, go!

644
00:50:11,207 --> 00:50:12,987
- MAN: One man down.
- MAN 2: Get up.

645
00:50:13,087 --> 00:50:14,467
- (WHISTLE BLOWS)
- MAN: OK, mark.

646
00:50:14,567 --> 00:50:15,867
Come on. Turn it up. Get back.

647
00:50:15,967 --> 00:50:18,307
- (MAN SHOUTS)
- MAN 2: Come on, boys.

648
00:50:18,407 --> 00:50:21,683
(MEN YELL INDISTINCTLY)

649
00:50:26,647 --> 00:50:28,683
MAN: Pass it! Pass it! Get out of
here!

650
00:50:29,687 --> 00:50:32,520
- Get onside!
- Get in there! Come on! Tackle!

651
00:50:36,327 --> 00:50:37,806
(BLOWS WHISTLE)

652
00:50:38,887 --> 00:50:39,876
MAN: Scrum.

653
00:50:41,647 --> 00:50:44,307
MAN: Come here, boys. Come on.
Scrum down. Tiffin in the middle here.

654
00:50:44,407 --> 00:50:46,238
MAN 2: Pack it in, boys. Come in
hard.

655
00:50:48,447 --> 00:50:50,107
MAN: It's out! It's out!

656
00:50:50,207 --> 00:50:52,907
- MAN 2: Push! Push out!
- MEN: Run!

657
00:50:53,007 --> 00:50:54,947
- Where's my runner?
- MAN: Get him, boys!

658
00:50:55,047 --> 00:50:56,627
- Come on, Billy!
- MAN: Go, Billy!

659
00:50:56,727 --> 00:50:58,763
- (MEN YELL)
- MAN: I'm with you, Billy.

660
00:50:59,927 --> 00:51:03,602
- Billy, go!
- Go, Streaky!

661
00:51:04,807 --> 00:51:06,923
(MEN CHEER)

662
00:51:13,167 --> 00:51:15,587
MAN: Victory to
the 1st Australian Tunnellers,

663
00:51:15,687 --> 00:51:18,027
six points to three.

664
00:51:18,127 --> 00:51:19,587
(ALL SING) d Parlez-vous?

665
00:51:19,687 --> 00:51:22,947
D Mademoiselle from Armentieres,
parlez-vous?

666
00:51:23,047 --> 00:51:24,667
D They'll do it for wine,
they'll do it for rum

667
00:51:24,767 --> 00:51:26,627
d They'll stick your finger
up your bum... d

668
00:51:26,727 --> 00:51:29,227
(LAUGHTER)
D Hinky-dinky, parlez-vous?

669
00:51:29,327 --> 00:51:32,707
D Oh, Mademoiselle from Armentieres,
parlez-vous?

670
00:51:32,807 --> 00:51:36,587
D Mademoiselle
from Armentieres, parlez-vous?

671
00:51:36,687 --> 00:51:38,907
D We're the boys from Townsville
and Dandenong

672
00:51:39,007 --> 00:51:40,747
d We're coming for you
with our donkey dongs

673
00:51:40,847 --> 00:51:42,827
d Hinky-dinky, parlez-vous?

674
00:51:42,927 --> 00:51:47,507
D Oh, Mademoiselle from Armentieres,
parlez-vous?

675
00:51:47,607 --> 00:51:50,787
D Mademoiselle
from Armentieres, parlez-vous?

676
00:51:50,887 --> 00:51:53,347
MAN: D She's really fat
and she's got big ears... d

677
00:51:53,447 --> 00:51:55,827
- What's up, Lieutenant?
- It's Captain, actually.

678
00:51:55,927 --> 00:51:57,787
Well done, sir.

679
00:51:57,887 --> 00:51:59,587
Thank you, Sergeant Fraser.

680
00:51:59,687 --> 00:52:01,907
- (MEN LAUGH)
- MAN: Hey, Sarge!

681
00:52:02,007 --> 00:52:03,281
As you were!

682
00:52:17,007 --> 00:52:18,867
We're moving up the line.

683
00:52:18,967 --> 00:52:20,707
We load up at midnight.

684
00:52:20,807 --> 00:52:23,507
How come you bastards get to leave
this shithole before us?

685
00:52:23,607 --> 00:52:25,467
(PLUMMY ACCENT)
Because only real soldiers

686
00:52:25,567 --> 00:52:28,267
get to move up the line. (LAUGHS)

687
00:52:28,367 --> 00:52:29,827
Where we heading, sir?

688
00:52:29,927 --> 00:52:32,387
Belgium.

689
00:52:32,487 --> 00:52:33,886
Hill 60.

690
00:52:40,767 --> 00:52:42,246
Better get your gear.

691
00:52:44,567 --> 00:52:46,637
Righto, you blokes. Let's go.

692
00:52:51,807 --> 00:52:53,787
ENGLISH SOLDIER:
Keep your heads down, lads.

693
00:52:53,887 --> 00:52:58,787
I nearly forgot - a present from
Fritz.

694
00:52:58,887 --> 00:53:00,707
He said to say,
‘‘Thanks for all your help."

695
00:53:00,807 --> 00:53:03,037
Cheers, mate.

696
00:53:07,127 --> 00:53:08,987
ENGLISH SOLDIER: You'll be right,
lads.

697
00:53:09,087 --> 00:53:10,645
AUSTRALIAN SOLDIER: Thanks, mate.

698
00:53:19,247 --> 00:53:20,726
(DISTANT EXPLOSION)

699
00:53:27,047 --> 00:53:29,800
(BABY CRIES)

700
00:53:31,807 --> 00:53:33,718
(EXPLOSIONS)

701
00:53:42,527 --> 00:53:44,165
Too early for the grey hen, sir?

702
00:53:48,327 --> 00:53:49,680
Never too early.

703
00:54:03,807 --> 00:54:06,526
(SHIVERS)

704
00:54:09,727 --> 00:54:11,467
- I'm right.
- Take 'em.

705
00:54:11,567 --> 00:54:13,267
You're just skin and bones.

706
00:54:13,367 --> 00:54:15,267
Come on, son.

707
00:54:15,367 --> 00:54:17,881
She'll send me another parcel
tomorrow, more than likely.

708
00:54:20,567 --> 00:54:22,319
(EXPLOSION)

709
00:54:24,687 --> 00:54:25,987
Decent fit.

710
00:54:26,087 --> 00:54:28,067
My Elsa's a first-rate knitter.

711
00:54:28,167 --> 00:54:30,627
When we get back, she'll have
probably knitted herself a new husband.

712
00:54:30,727 --> 00:54:31,707
(LAUGHS)

713
00:54:31,807 --> 00:54:34,027
Want to be a bit better-Iooking
than the old one.

714
00:54:34,127 --> 00:54:35,401
(LAUGHTER)

715
00:54:40,607 --> 00:54:42,867
Your boy's gonna make
a great prop forward.

716
00:54:42,967 --> 00:54:45,845
Don't I know it? And he's still
growing.

717
00:54:47,607 --> 00:54:49,040
You join up together?

718
00:54:51,167 --> 00:54:54,027
One of them recruiting blokes
came through town.

719
00:54:54,127 --> 00:54:56,347
Gets the young fella all excited
with his stories of adventure

720
00:54:56,447 --> 00:55:00,027
and seeing the Pyramids
and what have you.

721
00:55:00,127 --> 00:55:02,347
Never spent one bloody night
away from home

722
00:55:02,447 --> 00:55:03,987
and he's quit the pits and joined up.

723
00:55:04,087 --> 00:55:07,124
Elsa's nearly had bloody kittens,
hasn't she, Walt?

724
00:55:08,127 --> 00:55:09,467
Yep. (CHUCKLES)

725
00:55:09,567 --> 00:55:11,387
Well, you can't unjoin.

726
00:55:11,487 --> 00:55:14,307
So, after Walt went to bed,
I said to Elsa,

727
00:55:14,407 --> 00:55:16,787
‘‘I've looked after him all his life.
I'm not gonna stop now."

728
00:55:16,887 --> 00:55:19,720
I told her if I joined up,
I could bring him back safe.

729
00:55:21,167 --> 00:55:23,627
Elsa didn't know what was worse -

730
00:55:23,727 --> 00:55:26,560
her boy going off to the war by
himself, or both of us going.

731
00:55:29,687 --> 00:55:31,518
And she's been knitting like buggery
ever since.

732
00:55:42,167 --> 00:55:44,107
(SHELL EXPLODES)

733
00:55:44,207 --> 00:55:46,038
MAN: (SHOUTS)
Douse them flaming lights!

734
00:55:49,847 --> 00:55:52,267
Stay low! Stay low!

735
00:55:52,367 --> 00:55:55,882
(SHELLS EXPLODE, MEN SHOUT)

736
00:56:01,927 --> 00:56:03,918
Stay here!

737
00:56:14,847 --> 00:56:17,347
- Where's Fosse Way?
- It's north, that way!

738
00:56:17,447 --> 00:56:18,960
He said that way!

739
00:56:20,727 --> 00:56:22,147
Or south to Hill 60?

740
00:56:22,247 --> 00:56:25,027
Fraser! This way!

741
00:56:25,127 --> 00:56:26,467
(ARTILLERY SHELL WHINES)

742
00:56:26,567 --> 00:56:27,907
(SHELL EXPLODES)

743
00:56:28,007 --> 00:56:29,440
FRASER: Let's go!

744
00:56:32,767 --> 00:56:33,961
Keep down!

745
00:56:46,287 --> 00:56:48,187
Come on, boys!

746
00:56:48,287 --> 00:56:49,800
(ARTILLERY SHELL WHISTLES)

747
00:56:50,847 --> 00:56:52,041
(MAN YELLS)

748
00:56:56,087 --> 00:56:58,027
You alright, Walt?
Come on, come on, get up!

749
00:56:58,127 --> 00:56:59,526
Get up! Go!

750
00:57:04,167 --> 00:57:06,427
(ARTILLERY SHELLS WHISTLE)

751
00:57:06,527 --> 00:57:07,926
Where are the others?

752
00:57:17,687 --> 00:57:19,987
(COUGHING)

753
00:57:20,087 --> 00:57:21,918
FRASER: Sir!

754
00:57:23,727 --> 00:57:25,027
We left the bloody kids behind.

755
00:57:25,127 --> 00:57:26,107
Who's missing?

756
00:57:26,207 --> 00:57:28,067
Young Sneddon, Tiffin and Bacon.

757
00:57:28,167 --> 00:57:29,187
Walter!

758
00:57:29,287 --> 00:57:31,642
(SCREAMS) Walt!

759
00:57:34,527 --> 00:57:37,405
(DISTANT ARTILLERY FIRE)

760
00:57:40,207 --> 00:57:43,244
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS)

761
00:57:46,487 --> 00:57:48,557
- (MACHINE-GUN FIRE)
- Arggh!

762
00:57:49,727 --> 00:57:51,227
(MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

763
00:57:51,327 --> 00:57:53,079
(MEN YELL)

764
00:57:54,847 --> 00:57:55,867
(GRUNTS)

765
00:57:55,967 --> 00:57:58,606
(WALT GRUNTS AND SOBS)

766
00:58:02,247 --> 00:58:03,467
(MACHINE GUN FIRES)

767
00:58:03,567 --> 00:58:04,987
(WALT SCREAMS, SOBS)

768
00:58:05,087 --> 00:58:07,387
How can Fritz get to us?
We're behind the line, ain't we?

769
00:58:07,487 --> 00:58:08,827
He's got the high ground.

770
00:58:08,927 --> 00:58:10,027
(WALT WEEPS)

771
00:58:10,127 --> 00:58:12,867
(FLARE HISSES)

772
00:58:12,967 --> 00:58:14,667
JIM: (YELLS) Walter!

773
00:58:14,767 --> 00:58:16,200
Over here!

774
00:58:17,207 --> 00:58:18,507
Oh, fuck!

775
00:58:18,607 --> 00:58:19,907
We've missed it.

776
00:58:20,007 --> 00:58:20,987
(WALT SOBS)

777
00:58:21,087 --> 00:58:23,476
Sap's over to the right. About 25
yards.

778
00:58:28,807 --> 00:58:29,867
You ready?

779
00:58:29,967 --> 00:58:31,587
(MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

780
00:58:31,687 --> 00:58:32,907
(SCREAMS AND CRIES)

781
00:58:33,007 --> 00:58:34,707
Walt, we can't stay here, mate.

782
00:58:34,807 --> 00:58:37,526
(WEEPS CONTINUOUSLY)

783
00:58:43,447 --> 00:58:44,747
Tell you what,

784
00:58:44,847 --> 00:58:46,507
I'll go to the left and draw crabs.

785
00:58:46,607 --> 00:58:49,307
Soon as you hear that MG open up,
you run like buggery.

786
00:58:49,407 --> 00:58:51,318
Don't bloody stop
until you get to the sap!

787
00:58:52,927 --> 00:58:53,916
(WHISPERS) No.

788
00:58:55,127 --> 00:58:56,606
I'm twice as fast as you blokes.

789
00:58:58,007 --> 00:59:00,521
Probably make it before youse do.

790
00:59:02,247 --> 00:59:03,667
Come on, Walt!

791
00:59:03,767 --> 00:59:05,547
- (MACHINE GUN FIRES)
- (WALT YELPS)

792
00:59:05,647 --> 00:59:08,525
(REPEATED MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

793
00:59:13,967 --> 00:59:15,267
(MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

794
00:59:15,367 --> 00:59:17,187
- Stay low!
- Tiffin!

795
00:59:17,287 --> 00:59:18,867
Walt!

796
00:59:18,967 --> 00:59:20,267
Over here, mate!

797
00:59:20,367 --> 00:59:21,800
Come on.

798
00:59:22,967 --> 00:59:25,276
TIFFIN: Streaky's still out there!

799
00:59:27,047 --> 00:59:28,187
Billy!

800
00:59:28,287 --> 00:59:30,118
Billy Bacon!

801
00:59:32,727 --> 00:59:34,126
Streaky!

802
00:59:37,447 --> 00:59:38,960
BACON: (IN DISTANCE)
Did they get home?!

803
00:59:40,327 --> 00:59:41,726
They're home!

804
00:59:44,327 --> 00:59:46,987
- Streaky!
- Streaky!

805
00:59:47,087 --> 00:59:48,427
- Run!
- (MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

806
00:59:48,527 --> 00:59:50,707
- Billy!
- Go on, Billy!

807
00:59:50,807 --> 00:59:52,787
- Billy!
- Come on, Billy!

808
00:59:52,887 --> 00:59:54,627
- (MACHINE-GUN FIRE)
- Come on, Streaky!

809
00:59:54,727 --> 00:59:56,797
- Run, Billy!
- Come on!

810
00:59:58,807 --> 01:00:00,286
Arggh!

811
01:00:06,567 --> 01:00:08,205
(MOANS)

812
01:00:11,607 --> 01:00:13,747
Stretcher!

813
01:00:13,847 --> 01:00:15,758
Stretcher bearers!

814
01:00:57,967 --> 01:00:59,116
Streaky?

815
01:01:24,287 --> 01:01:27,245
Oh, this is God's
flamin' handiwork, is it?

816
01:01:39,687 --> 01:01:41,427
Grab his disc and pay book.

817
01:01:41,527 --> 01:01:43,279
We'll bury him in the morning.

818
01:01:57,447 --> 01:01:58,880
Come on, Frank.

819
01:02:02,407 --> 01:02:05,507
(MAN YELLS IN DISTANCE)

820
01:02:05,607 --> 01:02:09,361
MAN: (YELLS) Gas masks on now!
(BANGS TIN)

821
01:02:26,687 --> 01:02:28,467
Captain Woodward.

822
01:02:28,567 --> 01:02:30,319
1st Australian Tunnellers.

823
01:02:31,527 --> 01:02:34,667
- McBride!
- Captain McBride, actually.

824
01:02:34,767 --> 01:02:37,156
Where you been?
Been waiting for hours.

825
01:02:38,527 --> 01:02:40,404
(GUNFIRE)

826
01:02:42,207 --> 01:02:43,560
Hell of a place, eh?

827
01:02:47,247 --> 01:02:48,760
Your men can bunk down in there.

828
01:02:49,767 --> 01:02:52,507
Stow your kits.
Get a couple of hours' sleep.

829
01:02:52,607 --> 01:02:54,387
Couple of hours?

830
01:02:54,487 --> 01:02:56,027
Gee, sir. They'll turn soft on you.

831
01:02:56,127 --> 01:02:57,685
Come on!

832
01:03:09,287 --> 01:03:10,747
Have you seen the tunnels?

833
01:03:10,847 --> 01:03:14,840
You've got a big surprise
in store for you.

834
01:03:16,367 --> 01:03:17,707
Come on.

835
01:03:17,807 --> 01:03:19,320
Officers' dugout's down this way.

836
01:03:20,327 --> 01:03:22,716
I might just bunk down here
for the time being.

837
01:03:32,487 --> 01:03:34,627
TIFFIN: Wetter in here
than it is out there.

838
01:03:34,727 --> 01:03:37,587
WALT: More rats than in frickin'
France.

839
01:03:37,687 --> 01:03:39,279
FRASER: At least they're Belgian
rats.

840
01:03:40,327 --> 01:03:42,283
Change is as good as a holiday.

841
01:03:43,887 --> 01:03:45,639
WOODWARD: Keep your gas bags
within reach.

842
01:03:51,647 --> 01:03:53,524
At least we're back underground.

843
01:03:55,727 --> 01:03:57,365
(EXPLOSION)

844
01:03:58,447 --> 01:04:00,677
And we'll be staying underground.

845
01:04:02,207 --> 01:04:03,427
One way or another.

846
01:04:03,527 --> 01:04:06,107
What's that supposed to mean?

847
01:04:06,207 --> 01:04:09,267
This is how it goes from now on.

848
01:04:09,367 --> 01:04:11,147
We'll be dodging shells and shrapnel

849
01:04:11,247 --> 01:04:13,587
and out of the blue,
you cop a bullet in the guts

850
01:04:13,687 --> 01:04:15,166
like poor old Streaky.

851
01:04:16,847 --> 01:04:19,507
And it's no game of skill
down here, neither.

852
01:04:19,607 --> 01:04:22,787
Get eaten by rats,
get murdered by Fritz in the dark,

853
01:04:22,887 --> 01:04:25,640
or buried alive
for our fucking troubles.

854
01:04:36,767 --> 01:04:38,803
Well, that cheered us all up.

855
01:04:51,887 --> 01:04:53,559
(KNOCKS ON DOOR)

856
01:05:00,807 --> 01:05:02,399
Mr Waddell.

857
01:05:03,847 --> 01:05:05,838
Oliver.

858
01:05:07,527 --> 01:05:09,147
When do you set off?

859
01:05:09,247 --> 01:05:11,238
About three weeks.

860
01:05:14,727 --> 01:05:17,187
Right, well... you'd better come in,
then.

861
01:05:17,287 --> 01:05:18,627
Actually...

862
01:05:18,727 --> 01:05:20,206
...I'd like to ask you something.

863
01:05:25,607 --> 01:05:28,963
I would like your permission to write
to Marjorie while I'm overseas.

864
01:05:30,847 --> 01:05:32,267
And...

865
01:05:32,367 --> 01:05:35,245
...I'd like to spend some time with
her before I leave.

866
01:05:40,687 --> 01:05:42,227
- I know.
- Damn it.

867
01:05:42,327 --> 01:05:43,347
(SIGHS) Oh.

868
01:05:43,447 --> 01:05:45,165
- Emma.
- What?

869
01:05:46,367 --> 01:05:49,147
I'm gonna take my walk now,
if you'd care to come.

870
01:05:49,247 --> 01:05:51,044
Your walk?

871
01:05:52,887 --> 01:05:54,187
Aye.

872
01:05:54,287 --> 01:05:55,720
If you'd care to come?

873
01:05:59,247 --> 01:06:01,363
Oh... of course.

874
01:06:09,167 --> 01:06:11,397
They've never taken
a walk together in their lives.

875
01:06:23,767 --> 01:06:25,467
When I get back...

876
01:06:25,567 --> 01:06:28,559
...I'll take you walking every day.

877
01:06:39,327 --> 01:06:40,806
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

878
01:07:08,007 --> 01:07:09,042
Ja.

879
01:08:03,767 --> 01:08:05,564
SOLDIER: Can't see it.

880
01:08:08,287 --> 01:08:09,867
(FIRES GUN)

881
01:08:09,967 --> 01:08:11,187
Keep going.

882
01:08:11,287 --> 01:08:12,667
Mate, can I have a bo-peep?

883
01:08:12,767 --> 01:08:14,246
- Yeah, help yourself.
- Thanks.

884
01:08:16,847 --> 01:08:18,907
Hey, Pull Through.
Hill 60 - take a look.

885
01:08:19,007 --> 01:08:20,486
(GUNSHOT)

886
01:08:25,887 --> 01:08:27,267
Is that it?

887
01:08:27,367 --> 01:08:29,667
What were you expecting, Morris?
The fuckin' Matterhorn?

888
01:08:29,767 --> 01:08:30,747
(GUNSHOT)

889
01:08:30,847 --> 01:08:32,667
I was expecting something bigger
than a railway cuttin'.

890
01:08:32,767 --> 01:08:35,486
(BOTH LAUGH)

891
01:08:36,527 --> 01:08:37,907
(FIRES GUN)

892
01:08:38,007 --> 01:08:39,387
(FIRES MACHINE GUN)

893
01:08:39,487 --> 01:08:41,443
(WATER SLOSHES)

894
01:08:47,127 --> 01:08:49,147
WOODWARD: So, why ‘Berlin Sap'?

895
01:08:49,247 --> 01:08:50,867
McBRIDE: It goes so deep
under German lines,

896
01:08:50,967 --> 01:08:52,587
they reckon it almost reaches Berlin.

897
01:08:52,687 --> 01:08:56,227
WOODWARD: It's just mud and slurry.
Like sinking a mine in a bog.

898
01:08:56,327 --> 01:08:57,787
McBRIDE: Yeah, the blue clay's
further down.

899
01:08:57,887 --> 01:09:00,401
This whole area is below sea level.

900
01:09:02,247 --> 01:09:04,363
McBRIDE: Keeping the water out
was their main problem.

901
01:09:05,487 --> 01:09:06,907
Was?

902
01:09:07,007 --> 01:09:08,679
McBRIDE: Now it's ours.

903
01:09:18,367 --> 01:09:19,907
(WHISPERS) We're 90 feet down now.

904
01:09:20,007 --> 01:09:21,907
Right below German lines.

905
01:09:22,007 --> 01:09:23,827
Hill 60 is directly above us.

906
01:09:23,927 --> 01:09:27,681
Eh, eh, eh? Shh-shh. Shh.

907
01:09:29,767 --> 01:09:31,917
The blue clay of Flanders.

908
01:09:37,327 --> 01:09:38,787
Beautiful.

909
01:09:38,887 --> 01:09:41,867
Major North, 3rd Canadian Tunnellers.

910
01:09:41,967 --> 01:09:43,787
Fritz has set up in the swim sand.

911
01:09:43,887 --> 01:09:45,957
He can't get at us. Oh, no, no, no.

912
01:09:49,447 --> 01:09:51,085
If you will.

913
01:09:55,247 --> 01:09:58,907
53,000 pounds of
ammonal high explosive.

914
01:09:59,007 --> 01:10:01,157
8,000 pounds of guncotton.

915
01:10:02,767 --> 01:10:05,067
WOODWARD: I've never seen
anything like this before.

916
01:10:05,167 --> 01:10:07,840
No, nobody has. Nobody.

917
01:10:09,487 --> 01:10:12,867
500 feet down there
is a caterpillar mine.

918
01:10:12,967 --> 01:10:16,107
That one's 70,000 pounds.

919
01:10:16,207 --> 01:10:17,667
There's 21 of them.

920
01:10:17,767 --> 01:10:20,907
We've undermined the whole
of the Messines Ridge,

921
01:10:21,007 --> 01:10:23,646
nearly a million pounds of ammonal.

922
01:10:31,967 --> 01:10:33,387
NORTH: Mm-hm?

923
01:10:33,487 --> 01:10:35,467
You know, when this thing blows,

924
01:10:35,567 --> 01:10:38,923
it'll be the biggest explosion
the world's ever seen.

925
01:10:45,967 --> 01:10:49,267
Each mine has detonators and leads
running to the surface.

926
01:10:49,367 --> 01:10:50,507
WOODWARD: Mm-hm.

927
01:10:50,607 --> 01:10:52,947
McBRIDE: All we have to do
is keep the bloody thing dry

928
01:10:53,047 --> 01:10:54,747
and keep it secret from Fritz.

929
01:10:54,847 --> 01:10:58,635
No, no, no. No. Fritz has got no
idea.

930
01:11:02,287 --> 01:11:04,067
He thinks we're digging wells.

931
01:11:04,167 --> 01:11:06,027
(LAUGHS HOARSELY)

932
01:11:06,127 --> 01:11:08,083
Well, this'll finish the war.

933
01:11:09,327 --> 01:11:11,467
End it altogether.

934
01:11:11,567 --> 01:11:13,046
Think of that, huh?

935
01:11:15,327 --> 01:11:17,158
When do they plan to detonate?

936
01:11:18,167 --> 01:11:19,919
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

937
01:11:28,647 --> 01:11:30,160
They're pulling me out.

938
01:11:32,207 --> 01:11:34,163
It's up to you now.

939
01:11:37,887 --> 01:11:39,400
It's all up to you.

940
01:11:54,327 --> 01:11:55,840
Poor bugger.

941
01:11:57,207 --> 01:11:59,467
Yeah, he sleeps down here.

942
01:11:59,567 --> 01:12:01,637
He hasn't been to the surface
in three months.

943
01:12:05,167 --> 01:12:07,147
So, when are they gonna blow them?

944
01:12:07,247 --> 01:12:08,467
No-one knows.

945
01:12:08,567 --> 01:12:10,467
- Could be months away.
- What are they waiting for?

946
01:12:10,567 --> 01:12:13,001
Well, I'm a miner not a general...

947
01:12:14,047 --> 01:12:15,907
...but I reckon it's simple
arithmetic.

948
01:12:16,007 --> 01:12:20,307
If we blow the mines now,
we'll kill a few hundred Fritz at best.

949
01:12:20,407 --> 01:12:22,947
But if they think
there's an attack coming,

950
01:12:23,047 --> 01:12:27,387
they will stack those trenches
above us like bloody sardines.

951
01:12:27,487 --> 01:12:28,987
And kill thousands.

952
01:12:29,087 --> 01:12:31,627
Time it right,

953
01:12:31,727 --> 01:12:33,240
tens of thousands.

954
01:12:48,327 --> 01:12:49,507
(SCRAPES LOUDLY)

955
01:12:49,607 --> 01:12:50,801
(BANGING ECHOES)

956
01:12:54,007 --> 01:12:55,998
Nein.

957
01:13:08,807 --> 01:13:10,286
Ja.

958
01:13:20,767 --> 01:13:22,867
Jim, check every prop and every stay,

959
01:13:22,967 --> 01:13:25,707
starting here, all the way
to the bottom of the Berlin Sap.

960
01:13:25,807 --> 01:13:28,027
- Take Walter and Ginger.
- JIM: Sir.

961
01:13:28,127 --> 01:13:29,924
- I'll do the same for Caterpillar.
- Righto.

962
01:13:31,247 --> 01:13:34,947
Pull Through, there are
26 listening posts. Check them all.

963
01:13:35,047 --> 01:13:36,667
- Take Percy.
- Righto.

964
01:13:36,767 --> 01:13:40,267
Fraser, you check the water line.

965
01:13:40,367 --> 01:13:42,507
I want to know the depth
from the surface.

966
01:13:42,607 --> 01:13:44,547
I want to know
where the water is ending up.

967
01:13:44,647 --> 01:13:48,845
I want to know at exactly what depth
the sand becomes clay.

968
01:13:49,847 --> 01:13:52,267
- Take Tiffin with you.
- Sir.

969
01:13:52,367 --> 01:13:54,881
FRASER: Come on, Tiffin.

970
01:14:03,367 --> 01:14:04,787
(GUNSHOT)

971
01:14:04,887 --> 01:14:07,387
(MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

972
01:14:07,487 --> 01:14:09,079
- MAN: To the left.
- MAN 2: Yeah.

973
01:14:10,287 --> 01:14:13,245
MAN: Yep, yep, yep. That's another.
That's good. You got it.

974
01:14:14,247 --> 01:14:15,787
(GUNSHOT)

975
01:14:15,887 --> 01:14:17,366
MAN 3: Come out!

976
01:14:18,567 --> 01:14:20,239
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

977
01:14:45,167 --> 01:14:46,680
(GUNSHOT)

978
01:14:48,367 --> 01:14:50,801
(MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

979
01:15:13,767 --> 01:15:16,042
(GUNSHOT)

980
01:15:29,527 --> 01:15:32,107
(DISTANT SHOUTING)

981
01:15:32,207 --> 01:15:33,959
(GUNSHOT)

982
01:16:02,167 --> 01:16:04,362
(MAN SHOUTS ORDER IN GERMAN)

983
01:16:14,727 --> 01:16:16,206
(INHALES DEEPLY)

984
01:16:31,167 --> 01:16:33,147
(MUFFLED GUNFIRE)

985
01:16:33,247 --> 01:16:34,667
(MUFFLED MACHINE-GUN FIRE)

986
01:16:34,767 --> 01:16:36,519
- Nah. No, you're alright.
- (MACHINE-GUN FIRE SHARPENS)

987
01:16:37,647 --> 01:16:40,480
(GUNSHOTS CONTINUE)

988
01:16:51,007 --> 01:16:53,187
Bit bloody close.

989
01:16:53,287 --> 01:16:55,027
Sniper shell, by the size of it.

990
01:16:55,127 --> 01:16:56,719
Would have made a mess
of your melon.

991
01:16:57,807 --> 01:17:01,163
Saw one bloke hit by one of them -
half his head blown off.

992
01:17:02,527 --> 01:17:03,907
Only his smile left.

993
01:17:04,007 --> 01:17:05,326
(LAUGHS)

994
01:17:06,647 --> 01:17:08,558
(GUNSHOTS CONTINUE)

995
01:17:11,767 --> 01:17:13,439
How old are you?

996
01:17:15,247 --> 01:17:16,760
16.

997
01:17:18,047 --> 01:17:20,747
When they found out,
they made me a stretcher bearer.

998
01:17:20,847 --> 01:17:23,387
Keep me away from the horrors of war.

999
01:17:23,487 --> 01:17:24,907
(LAUGHS)

1000
01:17:25,007 --> 01:17:27,805
(BOTH LAUGH)

1001
01:17:29,207 --> 01:17:32,563
MAN: (SHOUTS) Stretcher bearers!
Stretcher bearers!

1002
01:17:33,567 --> 01:17:36,035
Over here.

1003
01:17:37,687 --> 01:17:39,166
MAN: Stretcher bearer!

1004
01:17:41,607 --> 01:17:44,075
- (FIRES GUN)
- Alright, come on. Let's go.

1005
01:17:50,087 --> 01:17:52,920
It's like trying to stop the tide
with a bloody sandcastle.

1006
01:17:59,767 --> 01:18:03,427
FRASER: Top level's mostly sand.
Clay starts around 30 feet.

1007
01:18:03,527 --> 01:18:06,107
Water seeps down,
pools above the clay.

1008
01:18:06,207 --> 01:18:09,427
Where it finds a tunnel,
it funnels down like a bloody creek.

1009
01:18:09,527 --> 01:18:11,987
We have 60 blokes manning the pumps
night and day

1010
01:18:12,087 --> 01:18:13,947
just to keep the water level down.

1011
01:18:14,047 --> 01:18:15,867
If we lose even a few of those men,

1012
01:18:15,967 --> 01:18:17,639
bloody mines'll be useless.

1013
01:18:21,607 --> 01:18:24,440
(WATER TRICKLES STEADILY)

1014
01:18:59,647 --> 01:19:01,126
(WHISPERS)
Where did they get this lot?

1015
01:19:02,167 --> 01:19:04,965
The sappers are getting it
wherever they can find it now, sir.

1016
01:19:06,407 --> 01:19:09,604
All the forests have been cut down
or stonkered by shellin'.

1017
01:19:11,967 --> 01:19:14,003
That's oak.

1018
01:19:15,447 --> 01:19:17,165
Me dad's a carpenter.

1019
01:19:18,247 --> 01:19:20,078
After the war, I'm gonna
get me apprenticeship.

1020
01:19:21,127 --> 01:19:22,879
Get out of them bloody pits.

1021
01:19:27,007 --> 01:19:29,867
More 'an likely, it came from
that ruined church in town.

1022
01:19:29,967 --> 01:19:31,587
Church?

1023
01:19:31,687 --> 01:19:34,565
Cathedral. Ypres Cathedral.

1024
01:19:36,247 --> 01:19:37,726
Probably.

1025
01:19:49,127 --> 01:19:52,187
- That's the lowest point in the sap.
- 90 feet, yeah.

1026
01:19:52,287 --> 01:19:54,947
What if we sink a shaft
directly to that point

1027
01:19:55,047 --> 01:19:56,507
and get the water out that way?

1028
01:19:56,607 --> 01:19:58,587
Canadians have tried it.
So have the Tommies.

1029
01:19:58,687 --> 01:20:00,747
The whole middle section is unstable.

1030
01:20:00,847 --> 01:20:04,587
Shaft walls collapse
after about six feet.

1031
01:20:04,687 --> 01:20:07,884
Besides, 90 feet vertical
is a bloody long way to move water.

1032
01:20:15,527 --> 01:20:18,147
We've got electricity
down there, don't we?

1033
01:20:18,247 --> 01:20:20,307
We propose sinking a shaft

1034
01:20:20,407 --> 01:20:23,707
down to a gallery
beneath the Berlin Sap, right here.

1035
01:20:23,807 --> 01:20:30,360
- Install electric pumps.
- Should free up 60 men at least.

1036
01:20:33,567 --> 01:20:35,125
Rutledge?

1037
01:20:37,567 --> 01:20:38,907
This is over 90 feet deep.

1038
01:20:39,007 --> 01:20:41,827
I shouldn't have thought an electric
pump would lift water that high...

1039
01:20:41,927 --> 01:20:43,347
WOODWARD: The new ones will, sir.

1040
01:20:43,447 --> 01:20:45,387
COLONEL: And this shaft
simply isn't feasible.

1041
01:20:45,487 --> 01:20:46,947
This is not a new idea, sir.

1042
01:20:47,047 --> 01:20:50,347
It's impossible to go through the wet
sand without the walls collapsing.

1043
01:20:50,447 --> 01:20:52,358
Have you been down there, Colonel?

1044
01:20:54,127 --> 01:20:58,307
Alright. That will be all.

1045
01:20:58,407 --> 01:21:02,241
Thank you, sir, and I apologise
for taking up your valuable time.

1046
01:21:05,887 --> 01:21:08,907
General, our plans differ
from the ones previously tried.

1047
01:21:09,007 --> 01:21:11,267
- How.
- We don't dig from the surface, sir.

1048
01:21:11,367 --> 01:21:14,987
We build the shaft head
20 feet below ground level.

1049
01:21:15,087 --> 01:21:18,067
We construct galleries large enough
to house all the tunnellers

1050
01:21:18,167 --> 01:21:19,547
and hide the blue clay.

1051
01:21:19,647 --> 01:21:21,587
Captain Woodward, 20 feet down

1052
01:21:21,687 --> 01:21:24,467
will put you right in the middle
of the quicksand.

1053
01:21:24,567 --> 01:21:26,947
You are wrong, Colonel!

1054
01:21:27,047 --> 01:21:30,483
It would set us just above
the wet sand. That's the point.

1055
01:21:33,647 --> 01:21:35,987
We'll use steel sections
to control the water

1056
01:21:36,087 --> 01:21:37,507
and stop the walls collapsing.

1057
01:21:37,607 --> 01:21:39,667
We use jacks from the roof
of the gallery

1058
01:21:39,767 --> 01:21:41,467
to force the steel sections
downwards.

1059
01:21:41,567 --> 01:21:45,507
And how many months or years
do we imagine that this folly will take?

1060
01:21:45,607 --> 01:21:47,837
- Rough estimate?
- GENERAL: How long?

1061
01:21:51,927 --> 01:21:54,805
Three weeks, give or take.

1062
01:21:59,807 --> 01:22:02,867
(ARTILLERY SHELL
WHISTLES AND EXPLODES)

1063
01:22:02,967 --> 01:22:04,446
MAN: Go, go, go!

1064
01:22:07,447 --> 01:22:09,267
(ARTILLERY SHELL
WHISTLES AND EXPLODES)

1065
01:22:09,367 --> 01:22:12,907
(SOLDIERS SHOUT AND SCREAM)

1066
01:22:13,007 --> 01:22:16,667
(ARTILLERY SHELL
WHISTLES AND EXPLODES)

1067
01:22:16,767 --> 01:22:19,827
MAN: Go! Keep going.

1068
01:22:19,927 --> 01:22:21,027
Aarggh!

1069
01:22:21,127 --> 01:22:26,307
MAN: Run! Run, boys, keep going.
Come on!

1070
01:22:26,407 --> 01:22:28,204
(EXPLOSIONS AND SHOUTING)

1071
01:22:29,287 --> 01:22:31,721
- (EXPLOSION)
- Aarggh!

1072
01:22:56,007 --> 01:22:57,599
One more.

1073
01:22:59,287 --> 01:23:00,402
Yep.

1074
01:23:04,167 --> 01:23:05,907
(CLANGING AND CLATTERING)

1075
01:23:06,007 --> 01:23:08,043
Shh. Shh.

1076
01:23:42,927 --> 01:23:44,427
We're nearly there.

1077
01:23:44,527 --> 01:23:46,947
Bucket it out. Get those jacks back
up.

1078
01:23:47,047 --> 01:23:49,027
Have that steel section
ready to go on my order.

1079
01:23:49,127 --> 01:23:50,879
Drive it further into the clay.

1080
01:24:16,087 --> 01:24:18,987
(MACHINE RATTLES)

1081
01:24:19,087 --> 01:24:20,725
It's going, sir.

1082
01:24:26,087 --> 01:24:27,805
(GUNSHOT)

1083
01:24:30,687 --> 01:24:32,882
GENERAL: Not exactly gushing.

1084
01:24:39,087 --> 01:24:40,987
What's happening, Tiffin?

1085
01:24:41,087 --> 01:24:42,827
- (MACHINE TICKS OVER)
- I don't know, sir.

1086
01:24:42,927 --> 01:24:44,804
It seems to be working.

1087
01:24:45,887 --> 01:24:48,720
- (GUNSHOT)
- No idea. It's working at that end.

1088
01:24:51,287 --> 01:24:53,547
(GUNSHOT)

1089
01:24:53,647 --> 01:24:55,285
COLONEL: Ridiculous.

1090
01:25:00,287 --> 01:25:02,357
Must be too much pressure.

1091
01:25:05,687 --> 01:25:07,200
I'm sure we...

1092
01:25:08,207 --> 01:25:10,243
Full report by the morning.

1093
01:25:12,487 --> 01:25:13,587
(SIGHS)

1094
01:25:13,687 --> 01:25:17,760
(WATER GURGLES)

1095
01:25:22,207 --> 01:25:24,163
- (ALL LAUGH)
- MAN: Yes!

1096
01:25:28,007 --> 01:25:30,646
(CLEARS THROAT)

1097
01:25:43,367 --> 01:25:44,747
(MACHINE CHUGS QUIETLY)

1098
01:25:44,847 --> 01:25:48,317
- What if the pump fails?
- We have backups standing by, sir.

1099
01:25:51,767 --> 01:25:54,187
Off the shaft head,
we've built two listening posts

1100
01:25:54,287 --> 01:25:55,507
and two diversion tunnels.

1101
01:25:55,607 --> 01:25:57,427
- What diversion tunnels?
- I'll show you, sir.

1102
01:25:57,527 --> 01:25:58,627
There's no need.

1103
01:25:58,727 --> 01:26:00,877
- It's no trouble.
- There is no need.

1104
01:26:06,847 --> 01:26:10,267
There's more activity
in the second diversion, sir.

1105
01:26:10,367 --> 01:26:12,947
I think Fritz is coming at us again.

1106
01:26:13,047 --> 01:26:14,587
WOODWARD: That means it's working.

1107
01:26:14,687 --> 01:26:18,027
He's been quiet for four minutes.

1108
01:26:18,127 --> 01:26:19,987
I reckon he could be ready to blow.

1109
01:26:20,087 --> 01:26:21,907
Let them.

1110
01:26:22,007 --> 01:26:23,747
Is it just the two of you down there?

1111
01:26:23,847 --> 01:26:25,147
- Just me, sir.
- Where's Walt?

1112
01:26:25,247 --> 01:26:27,907
He's up getting me a billy of tea.

1113
01:26:28,007 --> 01:26:29,627
What? He abandoned his post?

1114
01:26:29,727 --> 01:26:32,307
- No, he just...
- Put it on the report.

1115
01:26:32,407 --> 01:26:33,787
Why aren't you at your post?

1116
01:26:33,887 --> 01:26:37,038
- As I said, I think Fritz...
- Have you been ordered out?

1117
01:26:39,967 --> 01:26:41,507
Sir, the listeners have permission...

1118
01:26:41,607 --> 01:26:43,165
I know the orders, Captain!

1119
01:26:45,167 --> 01:26:47,476
Get back down there.

1120
01:26:50,487 --> 01:26:55,436
If you see Walt, you tell him...
you tell him not to...

1121
01:27:01,047 --> 01:27:03,083
Sir...

1122
01:27:05,767 --> 01:27:08,042
My dad likes a cup of tea
around now. (LAUGHS)

1123
01:27:12,527 --> 01:27:13,801
Jim.

1124
01:27:14,807 --> 01:27:15,796
WOODWARD: Jim!

1125
01:27:18,967 --> 01:27:21,435
Dad!

1126
01:27:23,207 --> 01:27:25,163
WALT: Dad!

1127
01:27:26,207 --> 01:27:28,987
WALT: Dad!

1128
01:27:29,087 --> 01:27:30,315
WOODWARD: Jim!

1129
01:27:34,007 --> 01:27:36,707
- (BREATHES HEAVILY)
- Dad!

1130
01:27:36,807 --> 01:27:38,240
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

1131
01:27:39,647 --> 01:27:44,084
WALT: Daddy, can you hear me? Dad!

1132
01:27:46,487 --> 01:27:49,001
(WALT CRIES LOUDLY)

1133
01:27:52,247 --> 01:27:58,067
Restore, establish and strengthen you
forever and ever, amen.

1134
01:27:58,167 --> 01:27:59,964
ALL: Amen.

1135
01:28:25,687 --> 01:28:28,360
(POIGNANT VIOLIN MUSIC)

1136
01:28:55,287 --> 01:28:57,198
Sir?

1137
01:29:01,767 --> 01:29:03,485
I've been wanting to give you this...

1138
01:29:04,967 --> 01:29:07,427
...for that girl of yours, sir.

1139
01:29:07,527 --> 01:29:09,677
I made it from that wood you liked...

1140
01:29:11,407 --> 01:29:12,840
...from the cathedral.

1141
01:29:16,087 --> 01:29:17,566
It's beautiful.

1142
01:29:35,047 --> 01:29:38,107
WOODWARD: This box was made
from the timbers of Ypres Cathedral

1143
01:29:38,207 --> 01:29:40,627
by a nice young chap named Frank
Tiffin.

1144
01:29:40,727 --> 01:29:42,867
I'm sure you'll get to meet him
after this is over

1145
01:29:42,967 --> 01:29:45,083
and thank him for his handiwork.

1146
01:30:14,087 --> 01:30:16,965
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

1147
01:31:36,087 --> 01:31:38,347
- What is it?
- Not sure.

1148
01:31:38,447 --> 01:31:42,486
15 degrees, about 20ft forward,
15ft down.

1149
01:31:51,287 --> 01:31:52,787
Nothing.

1150
01:31:52,887 --> 01:31:56,846
(COUGHS LOUDLY)

1151
01:32:11,007 --> 01:32:13,387
An attack tunnel?

1152
01:32:13,487 --> 01:32:17,467
No, it's different.

1153
01:32:17,567 --> 01:32:20,957
- I think it's some kind of shaft.
- Through the wet sand?

1154
01:32:25,207 --> 01:32:27,243
No. Can't be.

1155
01:32:28,927 --> 01:32:30,360
(COUGHS LIGHTLY)

1156
01:32:39,327 --> 01:32:41,557
(COUGHS)

1157
01:32:43,087 --> 01:32:47,478
- (COUGHS)
- (GUNFIRE)

1158
01:33:00,327 --> 01:33:02,067
(COUGHS)

1159
01:33:02,167 --> 01:33:03,964
MAN: Come on!

1160
01:33:06,087 --> 01:33:07,520
(GUNSHOT)

1161
01:33:23,767 --> 01:33:25,280
MAN: Come on!

1162
01:33:26,567 --> 01:33:29,604
(MAN YELLS INDISTINCTLY)

1163
01:33:42,247 --> 01:33:43,680
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

1164
01:33:47,047 --> 01:33:49,117
Du, nach oben.

1165
01:34:41,127 --> 01:34:44,107
Woodward? Woodward?

1166
01:34:44,207 --> 01:34:45,507
Woodward!

1167
01:34:45,607 --> 01:34:48,519
Captain Woodward, get up!

1168
01:34:54,487 --> 01:34:58,107
We're firing the mines Thursday
morning, just before dawn.

1169
01:34:58,207 --> 01:34:59,587
COLONEL: That's in 36 hours.

1170
01:34:59,687 --> 01:35:02,107
You'll be firing the Hill 60
and caterpillar mines.

1171
01:35:02,207 --> 01:35:05,267
McBride, you'll have
the back-up exploders.

1172
01:35:05,367 --> 01:35:06,707
Sir.

1173
01:35:06,807 --> 01:35:08,387
There'll be 21 blasts in all.

1174
01:35:08,487 --> 01:35:11,787
Yours will be the final two
in the sequence.

1175
01:35:11,887 --> 01:35:13,827
It's critical to the entire operation

1176
01:35:13,927 --> 01:35:18,947
that each mine goes off
precisely in the right order.

1177
01:35:19,047 --> 01:35:20,321
Yes, sir.

1178
01:35:22,127 --> 01:35:23,606
Firing orders.

1179
01:35:26,847 --> 01:35:29,042
MAN: Attention.

1180
01:36:04,407 --> 01:36:05,827
WOODWARD:
You were on listening duty?

1181
01:36:05,927 --> 01:36:09,667
All quiet, sir,
apart from a few squeaks.

1182
01:36:09,767 --> 01:36:12,587
- Rats?
- Probably.

1183
01:36:12,687 --> 01:36:17,507
Probably rats mating, sir,
by the sound of them.

1184
01:36:17,607 --> 01:36:19,107
Why do you say that?

1185
01:36:19,207 --> 01:36:22,244
They were kind of regular squeaks,
if you get my drift.

1186
01:36:25,447 --> 01:36:26,641
Where?

1187
01:36:28,207 --> 01:36:29,799
Lower listening post, Berlin Sap.

1188
01:36:44,247 --> 01:36:45,747
Windlass.

1189
01:36:45,847 --> 01:36:49,587
(SQUEAKING)

1190
01:36:49,687 --> 01:36:51,120
It's a shaft.

1191
01:36:52,487 --> 01:36:54,443
Right here.

1192
01:36:56,007 --> 01:36:57,987
That's right on top of the mine
at Hill 60.

1193
01:36:58,087 --> 01:37:00,027
We've been counting the squeaks
for 15 minutes now.

1194
01:37:00,127 --> 01:37:01,867
- I've calculated the depth...
- Yes.

1195
01:37:01,967 --> 01:37:03,667
63 feet, sir.

1196
01:37:03,767 --> 01:37:05,883
We blow in 10 hours.

1197
01:37:08,767 --> 01:37:10,347
When do you predict they'd hit the
mine?

1198
01:37:10,447 --> 01:37:14,587
At their current rate of progress,
nine hours, sir.

1199
01:37:14,687 --> 01:37:17,963
I hold you personally responsible.

1200
01:37:19,727 --> 01:37:21,558
Do what you have to do, Woodward.

1201
01:37:27,047 --> 01:37:29,787
- We're driving an attack tunnel.
- From where, sir?

1202
01:37:29,887 --> 01:37:32,747
Lower Berlin Sap listening post
to position 6-0.

1203
01:37:32,847 --> 01:37:34,599
- That's just above the mine.
- Yes.

1204
01:37:36,687 --> 01:37:37,987
That's suicidal.

1205
01:37:38,087 --> 01:37:40,078
That's an order, Sergeant.

1206
01:37:42,727 --> 01:37:43,987
Let's go.

1207
01:37:44,087 --> 01:37:45,918
Come on, let's go!

1208
01:38:31,847 --> 01:38:33,883
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

1209
01:38:47,567 --> 01:38:50,827
They're 10 feet forward, 15 feet up.

1210
01:38:50,927 --> 01:38:52,997
Morris.

1211
01:38:56,007 --> 01:38:58,547
- (EXPLOSIONS)
- McBRIDE: Resistance is good.

1212
01:38:58,647 --> 01:38:59,966
Check it again.

1213
01:39:02,127 --> 01:39:04,627
Were the leads reconnected
after the last test?

1214
01:39:04,727 --> 01:39:06,107
Mm-hm.

1215
01:39:06,207 --> 01:39:09,165
(CONTINUOUS ARTILLERY FIRE)

1216
01:39:13,247 --> 01:39:14,726
29 minutes.

1217
01:39:19,087 --> 01:39:20,566
I'm going back down.

1218
01:39:27,327 --> 01:39:28,667
Clear, please.

1219
01:39:28,767 --> 01:39:30,067
MAN: Out of the way!

1220
01:39:30,167 --> 01:39:33,045
(CONTINUOUS ARTILLERY FIRE)

1221
01:39:48,167 --> 01:39:49,566
MAN: Some tea coming.

1222
01:39:53,247 --> 01:39:56,547
(ARTILLERY SHELL WHISTLES)

1223
01:39:56,647 --> 01:39:57,867
(SHELL EXPLODES)

1224
01:39:57,967 --> 01:40:00,435
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

1225
01:40:26,607 --> 01:40:27,907
(WHISPERS) On three.

1226
01:40:28,007 --> 01:40:29,587
One...

1227
01:40:29,687 --> 01:40:30,707
...two...

1228
01:40:30,807 --> 01:40:31,787
...three.

1229
01:40:31,887 --> 01:40:32,907
(ALL INHALE)

1230
01:40:33,007 --> 01:40:34,627
(SILENCE)

1231
01:40:34,727 --> 01:40:38,083
(FAINT SCRATCHING)

1232
01:40:42,527 --> 01:40:44,387
(WHISPERS)
They're almost on top of us.

1233
01:40:44,487 --> 01:40:45,867
I've gotta set the charge.

1234
01:40:45,967 --> 01:40:49,307
No. That'll set off the main mine.

1235
01:40:49,407 --> 01:40:51,347
Wait till they're a few feet away.

1236
01:40:51,447 --> 01:40:52,947
Then use the camouflet.

1237
01:40:53,047 --> 01:40:54,526
A few feet?

1238
01:40:57,687 --> 01:40:59,667
Another four feet forward.

1239
01:40:59,767 --> 01:41:01,519
There's no time.

1240
01:41:04,167 --> 01:41:06,467
Four feet forward, Fraser.

1241
01:41:06,567 --> 01:41:08,797
Then set the charge.

1242
01:41:13,767 --> 01:41:15,280
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

1243
01:41:38,887 --> 01:41:41,003
(WHISPERS) Set the charge.

1244
01:41:42,647 --> 01:41:44,046
Finish the backing, boys.

1245
01:42:15,247 --> 01:42:16,646
(EXPLOSION)

1246
01:42:19,727 --> 01:42:21,957
They did it.

1247
01:42:25,687 --> 01:42:27,027
(IMITATES GERMAN ACCENT)
Guess what, Mutter?

1248
01:42:27,127 --> 01:42:28,947
I'm coming home. (LAUGHS)

1249
01:42:29,047 --> 01:42:30,027
Voomp!

1250
01:42:30,127 --> 01:42:32,587
(WHISTLES)

1251
01:42:32,687 --> 01:42:35,067
- Splat!
- (ALL LAUGH)

1252
01:42:35,167 --> 01:42:36,867
Go easy, boys.

1253
01:42:36,967 --> 01:42:38,547
Load up. Let's get out of here.

1254
01:42:38,647 --> 01:42:40,267
(LAUGHS)

1255
01:42:40,367 --> 01:42:42,547
Nein, nein! Schnell! Schnell!

1256
01:42:42,647 --> 01:42:44,747
Fritz will be landing
in Berlin right about now.

1257
01:42:44,847 --> 01:42:47,486
(LAUGHTER)

1258
01:42:52,647 --> 01:42:55,525
(DISTANT EXPLOSIONS CONTINUE)

1259
01:42:56,527 --> 01:42:58,427
- All clear below.
- Yes, sir.

1260
01:42:58,527 --> 01:43:00,347
The German shaft has been crumped.

1261
01:43:00,447 --> 01:43:02,358
All circuits are complete.

1262
01:43:11,567 --> 01:43:14,107
Five minutes!

1263
01:43:14,207 --> 01:43:16,227
MAN: (YELLS) Five minutes!

1264
01:43:16,327 --> 01:43:21,707
(MEN SHOUT DOWN THE LINE)
Five minutes! Five minutes!

1265
01:43:21,807 --> 01:43:24,924
Five minutes!

1266
01:43:26,847 --> 01:43:29,077
(MUTTERS QUIETLY)

1267
01:43:36,247 --> 01:43:38,761
(MEN MURMUR QUIETLY)

1268
01:43:49,567 --> 01:43:51,125
This is our great occasion.

1269
01:43:54,127 --> 01:43:55,958
- Yes, sir.
- Yes, sir.

1270
01:43:58,167 --> 01:43:59,964
Good luck.

1271
01:44:07,607 --> 01:44:09,747
(HEAVY BREATHING)

1272
01:44:09,847 --> 01:44:11,187
Four minutes to go.

1273
01:44:11,287 --> 01:44:12,587
- Did it easy.
- Yeah.

1274
01:44:12,687 --> 01:44:14,120
(RUMBLING)

1275
01:44:15,967 --> 01:44:18,003
Man buried!

1276
01:44:19,567 --> 01:44:21,347
- Who is it?
- It's Tiffin! He's back there!

1277
01:44:21,447 --> 01:44:22,747
Fuck.

1278
01:44:22,847 --> 01:44:24,280
Go! Go!

1279
01:44:29,447 --> 01:44:30,880
Tiffin!

1280
01:44:31,887 --> 01:44:33,161
Tiffin!

1281
01:44:34,167 --> 01:44:35,600
TIFFIN: Sarge?

1282
01:44:38,727 --> 01:44:40,627
FRASER: It's gonna take
some time to shift this.

1283
01:44:40,727 --> 01:44:42,399
I'll get them to hold the mine.

1284
01:45:02,407 --> 01:45:03,840
Well, what do we do?

1285
01:45:05,767 --> 01:45:07,200
Tiffin!

1286
01:45:09,127 --> 01:45:11,147
TIFFIN: (MUFFLED) Just go.

1287
01:45:11,247 --> 01:45:13,124
No point in all of us dying.

1288
01:45:19,687 --> 01:45:22,907
Fraser will get them to stop!

1289
01:45:23,007 --> 01:45:25,885
We'll come back when we know!

1290
01:45:29,127 --> 01:45:30,526
Righto!

1291
01:45:34,647 --> 01:45:36,046
'Bye, Tiffin!

1292
01:45:37,527 --> 01:45:40,405
Come on, Walt! Come on!

1293
01:45:42,567 --> 01:45:44,000
Cheerio, lads.

1294
01:45:45,527 --> 01:45:47,358
One minute!

1295
01:45:54,327 --> 01:45:55,667
Out of the way, please! Move!

1296
01:45:55,767 --> 01:45:56,947
(SHOUTS) Fuckin' move!

1297
01:45:57,047 --> 01:45:59,187
Fix bayonets!

1298
01:45:59,287 --> 01:46:01,107
FRASER: Out of the way! Move!

1299
01:46:01,207 --> 01:46:03,227
Out of the way! Make way!

1300
01:46:03,327 --> 01:46:04,667
Out of the fuckin' way!

1301
01:46:04,767 --> 01:46:06,907
(SHOUTS ORDERS)

1302
01:46:07,007 --> 01:46:08,759
20 seconds!

1303
01:46:17,807 --> 01:46:20,027
Out of the way! Move! Out of the way!

1304
01:46:20,127 --> 01:46:23,676
- Out of the fuckin' way!
- 15 seconds!

1305
01:46:25,247 --> 01:46:26,667
Tiffin's still in there.

1306
01:46:26,767 --> 01:46:28,644
- What happened?
- Collapse.

1307
01:46:32,447 --> 01:46:33,587
Sir, please.

1308
01:46:33,687 --> 01:46:36,326
10 seconds!

1309
01:46:37,327 --> 01:46:38,827
- He's still alive.
- Nine!

1310
01:46:38,927 --> 01:46:39,907
Eight!

1311
01:46:40,007 --> 01:46:41,587
We'd have him out in a few minutes.

1312
01:46:41,687 --> 01:46:42,907
Seven!

1313
01:46:43,007 --> 01:46:44,427
Six!

1314
01:46:44,527 --> 01:46:46,347
Five!

1315
01:46:46,447 --> 01:46:48,227
Four!

1316
01:46:48,327 --> 01:46:50,027
Three!

1317
01:46:50,127 --> 01:46:51,627
- FRASER: Woodward!
- Two!

1318
01:46:51,727 --> 01:46:54,627
(SHOUTS) For Christ's sake! It's
Tiffin!

1319
01:46:54,727 --> 01:46:56,160
Fire!

1320
01:47:11,647 --> 01:47:13,365
(EXPLOSION)

1321
01:47:26,767 --> 01:47:29,565
(CICADAS BUZZ, BIRDS CHIRP)

1322
01:47:38,487 --> 01:47:41,718
(MELANCHOLY MUSIC)

1323
01:48:07,607 --> 01:48:10,107
WOODWARD:
(WHISPERS) That's your heart.

1324
01:48:10,207 --> 01:48:11,547
Feel it?

1325
01:48:11,647 --> 01:48:13,267
(DISTANT EXPLOSION)

1326
01:48:13,367 --> 01:48:15,507
You're hearing your own heartbeat.

1327
01:48:15,607 --> 01:48:18,485
(RUMBLING INTENSIFIES)

1328
01:48:23,127 --> 01:48:26,005
(LOUD RUMBLING)

1329
01:48:32,047 --> 01:48:33,480
(SNIFFS)

1330
01:48:40,807 --> 01:48:41,987
(KNOCK ON DOOR)

1331
01:48:42,087 --> 01:48:44,920
McBRIDE: Woodward.
People are waiting.

1332
01:48:47,047 --> 01:48:49,322
Woody, are you alright?

1333
01:48:52,887 --> 01:48:54,798
- (DOORKNOB TURNS)
- I'm fine.

1334
01:48:56,207 --> 01:48:57,959
I'll be out shortly.

1335
01:49:20,567 --> 01:49:22,046
You right?

